# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: metrics-cardinality
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] In mathematics, **cardinality** is an inherent property of sets, roughly meaning the number of individual objects they contain, which may be infinite.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The concept is understood through one-to-one correspondences between sets.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] That is, if their objects can be paired such that each object has a pair, and no object is paired more than once.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Two sets are said to be ***equinumerous*** or *have the same cardinality* if there exists a one-to-one correspondence between them.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Otherwise, under the axiom of choice, one of the two sets must be equinumerous with a strict subset of the other and is said to be *strictly smaller* than it; the other set is *strictly larger*.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Using this concept, it is possible to show there are different sizes of infinity.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] A set is countably infinite if it can be placed in one-to-one correspondence with the set of natural numbers ⁠ $\{1,2,3,4,\cdots \}$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] For example, the set of even numbers ⁠ $\{2,4,6,\cdots \}$ ⁠ and the set of rational numbers are countable.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Uncountable sets are those strictly larger than the set of natural numbers.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The set of all real numbers and the powerset of the set of natural numbers are proven to be uncountable by so-called diagonal arguments.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Cantor's theorem generalizes these arguments to show there is an infinite hierarchy of infinities.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] For finite sets, cardinality recovers the usual concept of size as "number of elements." However, it is more often difficult to ascribe "sizes" to infinite sets.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] A system of cardinal numbers can be developed to extend the role of natural numbers in answering "how many".
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Most commonly, the Aleph numbers ⁠ $\aleph _{0},\aleph _{1},\aleph _{2},...\aleph _{\omega },\aleph _{\omega +1}...$ ⁠ are used, since their definition naturally extends the process of counting, and it can be shown that every infinite set has cardinality equivalent to some Aleph.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The set of natural numbers has cardinality ⁠ $\aleph _{0}$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The question of whether the real numbers have cardinality ⁠ $\aleph _{1}$ ⁠ is known as the continuum hypothesis, which has been shown to be both unprovable and undisprovable in standard set theories such as Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Alternative set theories and additional axioms give rise to different properties and have often strange or unintuitive consequences.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] However, every theory of cardinality using standard logical foundations of mathematics admits Skolem's paradox.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The basic concepts of cardinality go back as early as the 6th century BCE, and there are several close encounters with it throughout history, however, the results were generally dismissed as paradoxical.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] It is considered to have been first introduced formally to mathematics by Georg Cantor at the turn of the 20th century.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Cantor's theory of cardinality was then formalized, popularized, and explored by many influential mathematicians of the time, and has since become a fundamental concept of mathematics.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Cardinality is an inherent property of sets which defines their size, roughly meaning the number of individual objects they contain.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Fundamentally however, it is different from the concepts of number or counting as the cardinalities of two sets can be compared without referring to their number of elements, or defining number at all.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] For example, in the image above, a set of apples is compared to a set of oranges such that every fruit is used exactly once which shows these two sets have the same cardinality, even if one does not know how many of each there are.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Thus, cardinality is measured by putting sets in so-called one-to-one correspondence: each object in one set can be assigned a dedicated "pair" in the other, and no object from either set left unpaired.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] If it is possible, the sets are said to have the *same cardinality*, and if not, one set is said to be *strictly larger* or *strictly smaller* than the other.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The basic concepts of cardinality are developed in terms of sets and functions, which are more abstract than their counterparts outside of mathematics.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Informally, a set can be understood as any collection of objects, usually represented with curly braces.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] For example, ⁠ $S=\{1,2,3\}$ ⁠ specifies a set, called ⁠ S ⁠, which contains the numbers 1, 2, and 3.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The symbol ⁠ $\in$ ⁠ represents set membership, for example ⁠ $1\in S$ ⁠ says "1 is a member of the set ⁠ S ⁠" which is true by the definition of ⁠ S ⁠ above.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Here ⁠ S ⁠ is finite, but that is not a requirement in general.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The only requirement for a set is that it is well-defined.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] That is, for any object, ⁠ x ⁠, one can determine whether ⁠ x ⁠ belongs to that set ⁠ $(x\in S)$ ⁠, or ⁠ x ⁠ does not belong to that set ⁠ $(x\notin S)$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] One example of an infinite set is the set of all natural numbers ⁠ $\{1,2,3,\cdots \}$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] A function, or correspondence, maps each member of one set to a unique member of another, often represented with an arrow diagram.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] For example, the adjacent table depicts several functions which map sets of natural numbers to sets of letters.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] If a function does not map two members to the same place, it is called injective.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] If a function covers every member in the output set, it is called surjective.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] If a function is both injective and surjective, it is called bijective or a one-to-one correspondence.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Functions are not limited to those one can draw an arrow diagram for, so long as the function is well-defined.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] That is, for each possible input, the output is defined.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The term *cardinality* originates from the post-classical Latin *cardo* ("to hinge"), which referred to something central or pivotal, both literally and metaphorically.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] This passed into medieval Latin and then into English, where *cardinal* came to describe things considered to be, in some sense, fundamental, such as, *cardinal sins*, *cardinal directions*, and (in linguistics) *cardinal numbers*.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The last of which referred to numbers used for counting (e.g., *one*, *two*, *three*), as opposed to *ordinal numbers*, which express order (e.g., *first, second, third*), and *nominal numbers* used for labeling without meaning (e.g., jersey numbers and serial numbers).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] In mathematics, the notion of cardinality was first introduced by German mathematician Georg Cantor in the late 19th century, who used the term *Mächtigkeit*, which may be translated as "magnitude" or "power", though Cantor credited the term to a work by Jakob Steiner on projective geometry.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Around 1930, the terms *cardinality* and *cardinal number* were adopted from the grammatical sense, and later translations would use these terms.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] An intuitive relationship between two sets having the "same size" is that their objects can be paired one-to-one.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] That is, if each object in one set can be assigned a dedicated "pair" in the other, and no object from either set left unpaired, there are the same number of objects in each set.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] A one-to-one pairing between two sets defines a bijective function between them by mapping each object to its pair.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Similarly, a bijection between two sets defines a pairing of their elements by pairing each object with the one it maps to.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Therefore, these notions of "pairing" and "bijection" are, at least intuitively, equivalent.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Two sets are said to have the *same cardinality* or be *equinumerous* if their members can be paired one-to-one.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] That is, if there exists a function between them which is bijective.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] This is often written as ⁠ $A\sim B$ ⁠, or ⁠ $A\approx B$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Alternatively, these sets may be said to be *equivalent*, *similar*, *equipotent*, or *equipollent*.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The property for finite sets that "the whole is greater than the part" is no longer true for infinite sets, and the existence of surjections or injections that do not work does not prove that there is no bijection.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] For example, the function ⁠ g ⁠ from ⁠ $\mathbb {N}$ ⁠ to ⁠ E ⁠, defined by multiplying by 4, ⁠ $g(n)=4n$ ⁠, is injective, but not surjective (since 2, for instance, is not mapped to).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Further, the function ⁠ h ⁠ from ⁠ $\mathbb {N}$ ⁠ to ⁠ E ⁠, defined by rounding down to the nearest even number, ⁠ $h(n)=2\operatorname {floor} (n/2)$ ⁠ (cf.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] *floor function*), is surjective, but not injective, (since 0 and 1 for instance both map to 0).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Neither ⁠ g ⁠ nor ⁠ h ⁠ can challenge ⁠ $E\sim \mathbb {N}$ ⁠, which was established by the existence of ⁠ f ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] A fundamental result in developing a theory of cardinality is that equinumerosity forms an equivalence relation—that is, a relation satisfying the same three basic properties as equality: reflexivity, symmetry, and transitivity.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Reflexivity, the property that every set has the same cardinality as itself ⁠ $(A\sim A)$ ⁠, follows from the identity function: for any set ⁠ A ⁠, the function that maps each element to itself is a bijection from ⁠ A ⁠ to **⁠ A ⁠**.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Symmetry, the property that, if ⁠ A ⁠ has the same cardinality as ⁠ B ⁠ ⁠ $(A\sim B)$ ⁠, then ⁠ B ⁠ has the same cardinality as ⁠ A ⁠ ⁠ $(B\sim A)$ ⁠, holds because any bijection ⁠ $f:A\to B$ ⁠ has an inverse function ⁠ $f^{-1}:B\to A$ ⁠, which is also bijective.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Since equinumerosity satisfies all three properties, it is an equivalence relation.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] This means that it groups sets into equivalence classes—groups of sets that are all equinumerous with one another—where each group defines a possible size of a set.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] This motivates the notion of cardinal numbers, which are representatives that stand for the "size" of each group, developed in the section below.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] A set ⁠ A ⁠ is not larger than a set ⁠ B ⁠ if it can be mapped into ⁠ B ⁠ without overlap.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] That is, the cardinality of ⁠ A ⁠ is less than or equal to the cardinality of ⁠ B ⁠ if there is an injective function from ⁠ A ⁠ to **⁠ B ⁠**, or equivalently, if there is a surjection from **⁠ B ⁠** to ⁠ A ⁠ (or ⁠ A ⁠ is empty).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] For example, if ⁠ A ⁠ has four elements and ⁠ B ⁠ has five, then the following are true ⁠ $A\preceq A$ ⁠, ⁠ $A\preceq B$ ⁠, and ⁠ $A\prec B$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The basic properties of an inequality are reflexivity (for any ⁠ a ⁠, ⁠ $a\leq a$ ⁠), transitivity (if ⁠ $a\leq b$ ⁠ and ⁠ $b\leq c$ ⁠, then ⁠ $a\leq c$ ⁠) and antisymmetry (if ⁠ $a\leq b$ ⁠ and ⁠ $b\leq a$ ⁠, then ⁠ $a=b$ ⁠).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Cardinal inequality ⁠ $(\preceq )$ ⁠ as defined above is reflexive since the identity function is injective, and is transitive by function composition.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Antisymmetry—the fact that, given injections in both directions, then one can find a bijection—is non-trivial, and is the content of the so-called Schröder–Bernstein theorem.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Given injections in both directions (⁠ $f:A\to B$ ⁠, and ⁠ $g:B\to A$ ⁠), take set ⁠ A ⁠ and "color" each point blue.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Then take the image of set ⁠ B ⁠ on ⁠ A ⁠ after the injection—that is, the set of points that the injection projects on to—and color those red.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Then take the image of ⁠ A ⁠ on this image of ⁠ B ⁠, and color those points blue again.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] By recursively alternating the images of these sets, one obtains a "coloring" of the original set (see illustration).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] For each point, it either stops at some finite step—and thus is definitively colored blue or red—or continues switching indefinitely.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Of the points in ⁠ A ⁠ that are definitively colored blue, map them into the next recursive image (i.e. by applying ⁠ f ⁠ then ⁠ g ⁠), leaving all other points in place.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] This transforms the set ⁠ A ⁠ into exactly the image of ⁠ B ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Taking this transformation, followed by the inverse of ⁠ g ⁠, gives a bijection from ⁠ A ⁠ to ⁠ B ⁠ (since ⁠ g ⁠ is injective and surjective on its image, its inverse is bijective).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] A further property of cardinal inequality is totality, which says that any two sets are comparable.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] That is, for any ⁠ a ⁠ and ⁠ b ⁠, either ⁠ $a\leq b$ ⁠ or ⁠ $b\leq a$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] A full proof of which requires concepts introduced later, however the argument can be briefly summarized as follows.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Every well-ordered set is isomorphic to a unique ordinal number, called the order type of the set.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] By the well-ordering theorem, every set can be well-ordered.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Then, by comparing their order types, one can show that ⁠ $A\preceq B$ ⁠ or ⁠ $B\preceq A$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] This fact is equivalent to the axiom of choice.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] A set is called *countable* if it is finite or has a bijection with the set of natural numbers ⁠ $(\mathbb {N} )$ ⁠, in which case it is called *countably infinite*.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The term *denumerable* is also sometimes used for countably infinite sets.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] For example, the set of all even natural numbers is countable, and therefore has the same cardinality as the whole set of natural numbers, even though it is a proper subset.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Similarly, the set of square numbers is countable, which was considered paradoxical for hundreds of years before modern set theory (cf.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] However, several other examples have historically been considered surprising or initially unintuitive since the rise of set theory.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] On the left, a version for the positive rational numbers.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The rational numbers ⁠ $(\mathbb {Q} )$ ⁠ are those which can be expressed as the quotient or fraction ⁠ ${\tfrac {p}{q}}$ ⁠ of two integers.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The rational numbers can be shown to be countable by considering the set of fractions as the set of all ordered pairs of integers, which can be visualized as the set of all integer points on a grid.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Then, an intuitive function can be described by drawing a line in a repeating pattern, or spiral, which eventually goes through each point in the grid.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] For example, going through each diagonal on the grid for positive fractions, or through a lattice spiral for all integer pairs.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] These over-cover the rationals, since, for example, the fractions ⁠ $\textstyle {\frac {2}{4}},\,{\frac {3}{6}},\,{\frac {4}{8}},\,\dots$ ⁠ all get mapped to ⁠ $\textstyle {\frac {1}{2}}$ ⁠, as the grid method treats these all as distinct ordered pairs.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] So this function shows ⁠ $\vert \mathbb {Q} \vert \leq \vert \mathbb {N} \vert$ ⁠ not ⁠ $\vert \mathbb {Q} \vert =\vert \mathbb {N} \vert$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] This can be corrected by "skipping over" these numbers in the grid, using the Schröder–Bernstein theorem, or by designing a function which does this naturally, for example using the Calkin–Wilf tree.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] A number is called algebraic if it is a solution of some polynomial equation with integer coefficients.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] For example, the square root of two ⁠ ${\sqrt {2}}$ ⁠ is a solution to ⁠ $x^{2}-2=0$ ⁠, and the rational number ⁠ $p/q$ ⁠ is the solution to ⁠ $qx-p=0$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Conversely, a number which cannot be the root of any polynomial is called transcendental.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Two examples include Euler's number (*e*) and pi (π).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] In general, proving a number is transcendental is considered to be very difficult, and only a few classes of transcendental numbers are known.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] However, it can be shown that the set of algebraic numbers is countable by ordering the polynomials lexicographically (for example, see *Cantor's first set theory article § The proofs*).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Since the set of algebraic numbers is countable while the real numbers are uncountable (shown in the following subsection), the transcendental numbers must form the vast majority of real numbers, even though they are individually much harder to identify.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] That is to say, almost all real numbers are transcendental.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Hilbert's paradox of the Grand Hotel is a popular thought experiment devised by the German mathematician David Hilbert to illustrate a counterintuitive property of countably infinite sets, allowing them to have the same cardinality as a proper subset of themselves.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The scenario begins by imagining a hotel with an infinite number of rooms, one for each natural number, all of which are occupied.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] But then a new guest walks in asking for a room.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The hotel accommodates by moving the occupant of room 1 to room 2, the occupant of room 2 to room 3, room 3 to room 4, and in general, room n to room n+1.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Then every guest still has a room, but room 1 is open for the new guest.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Then, the scenario continues by imagining an infinitely long bus of new guests seeking a room.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The hotel accommodates by moving the person in room 1 to room 2, room 2 to room 4, and in general, room n to room 2n.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Thus, all the even-numbered rooms are occupied, but all the odd-numbered rooms are vacant, leaving room for the infinite bus of new guests.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The scenario continues further by assuming an infinite number of these infinite buses arrive at the hotel, and showing that the hotel is still able to accommodate.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Finally, an infinite bus which has a seat for every real number arrives, and the hotel is no longer able to accommodate.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] A set is called *uncountable* if it is not countable; that is, it is infinite and strictly larger than the set of natural numbers.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The usual first example of this is the set of real numbers ⁠ $(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠, which can be understood as the set of all numbers on the number line.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] One method of proving that the reals are uncountable is called Cantor's diagonal argument, credited to Cantor for his 1891 proof, though his method differs from the more common presentation.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] It begins by assuming, by contradiction, that there is some one-to-one mapping between the natural numbers and the set of real numbers between 0 and 1 (the interval ⁠ $[0,1]$ ⁠).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Then, take the decimal representation of each real number, for example, ⁠ $0.5772...$ ⁠ with a leading zero followed by any sequence of digits.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The number 1 is included in this set since 1 = 0.999...
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Considering these real numbers in a list, it is always possible to create a new number such that the first digit of the new number is different from that of the first number in the list, the second digit is different from the second number in the list, and so on.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The new number must also have a unique decimal representation, that is, it cannot end in repeating nines or repeating zeros.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] For example, if the digit is not 2, make the digit of the new number 2, and if it was 2, make it 3.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Then, this new number will be different from each of the numbers in the list by at least one digit, and therefore must not be in the list.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] This shows that the real numbers cannot be put into a one-to-one correspondence with the naturals, and thus must be strictly larger.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Another classical example of an uncountable set, established using a related reasoning, is the power set of the natural numbers, denoted ⁠ ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] This is the set of all subsets of ⁠ $\mathbb {N}$ ⁠, including the empty set and ⁠ $\mathbb {N}$ ⁠ itself.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The method is much closer to Cantor's original diagonal argument.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Again, assume by contradiction that there exists a one-to-one correspondence ⁠ f ⁠ between ⁠ $\mathbb {N}$ ⁠ and ⁠ ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ ⁠, so that every subset of ⁠ $\mathbb {N}$ ⁠ is assigned to some natural number.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] These subsets are then placed in a list, in the order defined by ⁠ f ⁠ (see image).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] If ⁠ $1\in f(1)$ ⁠, then ⁠ $1\notin T$ ⁠, that is, if 1 is in the first subset of the list, then 1 is *not* in the subset ⁠ T ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Further, if ⁠ $2\notin f(2)$ ⁠, then ⁠ $2\in T$ ⁠, that is if the number 2 is not in the second subset of the list, then 2 *is* in the subset ⁠ T ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Then in general, for each natural number ⁠ n ⁠, ⁠ $n\in T$ ⁠ if and only if ⁠ $n\notin f(n)$ ⁠, meaning ⁠ n ⁠ is put in the subset ⁠ T ⁠ only if the nth subset in the list does not contain the number ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Then, for each natural number ⁠ n ⁠, ⁠ $T\neq f(n)$ ⁠, meaning, ⁠ T ⁠ is not the nth subset in the list, for any number ⁠ n ⁠, and so it cannot appear anywhere in the list defined by ⁠ f ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Since ⁠ f ⁠ was chosen arbitrarily, this shows that every function from ⁠ $\mathbb {N}$ ⁠ to ⁠ ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ ⁠ must be missing at least one element, therefore no such bijection can exist, and so ⁠ ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ ⁠ must be not be countable.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] These two sets, ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠ and ⁠ ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ ⁠ can be shown to have the same cardinality (by, for example, assigning each subset to a decimal expansion) called the cardinality of the continuum.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Cantor's theorem generalizes the second theorem above, showing that every set is strictly smaller than its powerset.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] In broad strokes, the proof goes as follows: Given a set ⁠ A ⁠, assume by contradiction that there is a bijection ⁠ f ⁠ from ⁠ A ⁠ to ⁠ ${\mathcal {P}}(A)$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Then, the subset ⁠ $T\subseteq A$ ⁠ given by taking the negation of the "diagonal", formally, ⁠ $T=\{a\in A:a\notin f(a)\}$ ⁠, cannot be in the list.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Therefore, every function is missing at least one element, and so ⁠ $\vert A\vert <\vert {\mathcal {P}}(A)\vert$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Further, since ⁠ ${\mathcal {P}}(A)$ ⁠ is itself a set, the argument can be repeated to show ⁠ $\vert A\vert <\vert {\mathcal {P}}(A)\vert <\vert {\mathcal {P}}({\mathcal {P}}(A))\vert$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Taking ⁠ $A=\mathbb {N}$ ⁠, this shows that ⁠ ${\mathcal {P}}({\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} ))$ ⁠ is even larger than ⁠ ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ ⁠, which was already shown to be uncountable.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Repeating this argument shows that there are infinitely many "sizes" of infinity.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] In the above sections, "the cardinality of a set" was described relationally.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] In other words, one set could be compared to another, intuitively comparing their "size".
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Cardinal numbers are a means of measuring this "size" more explicitly.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] For finite sets, this is simply the natural number found by counting the elements.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] This number is called the *cardinal number* of that set, or simply *the cardinality* of that set.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The cardinal number of a set ⁠ A ⁠ is generally denoted by ⁠ $\vert A\vert$ ⁠, with a vertical bar on each side, though it may also be denoted by ⁠ A ⁠, ⁠ $\operatorname {card} (A)$ ⁠, or ⁠ $\#A$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] For infinite sets, "cardinal number" is somewhat more difficult to define formally.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] However, cardinal numbers are not usually thought of in terms of their formal definition, but immaterially in terms of their arithmetic/algebraic properties.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Commonly in mathematics, if a relation satisfies the properties of an equivalence relation, the objects used to materialize this relation are equivalence classes, each of which group objects equivalent to one another.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] These equivalence classes are called the *Frege–Russell* cardinal numbers.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Thus, due to John von Neumann, it is more common to assign representatives of these classes.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Given a basic sense of natural numbers, a set is said to have cardinality ⁠ n ⁠ if it can be put in one-to-one correspondence with the set ⁠ $\{1,\,2,\,\dots ,\,n\}$ ⁠, analogous to counting its elements.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] For example, the set ⁠ $S=\{A,B,C,D\}$ ⁠ has a natural correspondence with the set ⁠ $\{1,2,3,4\}$ ⁠, and therefore is said to have cardinality 4.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Other terminologies include "Its cardinality is 4" or "Its cardinal number is 4".
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] In formal contexts, the natural numbers can be understood as some construction of objects satisfying the Peano axioms—a list of properties, such that any system satisfying these properties is, in a certain sense, just like the natural numbers.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Showing that such a correspondence exists is not always trivial.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Combinatorics is the area of mathematics primarily concerned with counting, both as a means and as an end to obtaining results, and certain properties of finite structures.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The notion cardinality of finite sets is closely tied to many basic combinatorial principles, and provides a set-theoretic foundation to recover them.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] It can be shown by induction on the possible sizes of sets that finite cardinality corresponds uniquely with natural numbers (cf.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] *Finite set § Uniqueness of cardinality*).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] This is related to several other concepts, verifying Hume's principle and the basis of bijective proofs, and is equivalent to a certain formulation of the pigeonhole principle, that a finite set cannot be put in one to one correspondence with a proper subset of itself.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The addition principle asserts that given disjoint sets ⁠ A ⁠ and ⁠ B ⁠, ⁠ $\vert A\cup B\vert =\vert A\vert +\vert B\vert$ ⁠, intuitively meaning that the sum of the parts is equal to the whole.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The multiplication principle asserts that given two sets ⁠ A ⁠ and ⁠ B ⁠, ⁠ $\vert A\times B\vert =\vert A\vert \cdot \vert B\vert$ ⁠, intuitively meaning that there are ⁠ $\vert A\vert \cdot \vert B\vert$ ⁠ ways to pair objects from these sets.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Both of these can be proven by a bijective proof, together with induction.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The more general result is the inclusion–exclusion principle, which defines how to count the number of elements in overlapping sets.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Naturally, a set is defined to be finite if it is empty or can be put in correspondence with the set ⁠ $\{1,\,2,\,\dots ,\,n\}$ ⁠, for some natural number ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The aleph numbers are a sequence of cardinal numbers that represent the sizes of infinite sets, denoted with an aleph ⁠ $\aleph$ ⁠, the first letter of the Hebrew alphabet.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The first aleph number is ⁠ $\aleph _{0}$ ⁠, called "aleph-nought", "aleph-zero", or "aleph-null", which represents the cardinality of the set of all natural numbers: ⁠ $\aleph _{0}=\vert \mathbb {N} \vert =\vert \{0,1,2,3,\cdots \}\vert$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Then, ⁠ $\aleph _{1}$ ⁠ represents the next largest cardinality, then ⁠ $\aleph _{2}$ ⁠, and so on.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The most common way this is formalized in set theory is through Von Neumann ordinals, known as Von Neumann cardinal assignment.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Ordinal numbers generalize the notion of *order* to infinite sets.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] For example, 2 comes after 1, denoted ⁠ $1<2$ ⁠, and 3 comes after both, denoted ⁠ $1<2<3$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Then, one defines a new number, ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠, which comes after every natural number, denoted ⁠ $1<2<3<\cdots <\omega$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Further ⁠ $\omega <\omega +1<\dots <\omega +\omega =\omega \cdot 2$ ⁠, and so on.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Defining ⁠ ${\displaystyle \omega$ ⁠ gives ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠ the desired property of being the smallest ordinal greater than all finite ordinal numbers.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Since ⁠ $\omega \sim \mathbb {N}$ ⁠ by the natural correspondence, one may define ⁠ $\aleph _{0}$ ⁠ as the set of all finite ordinals.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Then, ⁠ $\aleph _{1}$ ⁠ is the set of all countable ordinals (all ordinals ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠ with cardinality ⁠ $\vert \alpha \vert \leq \aleph _{0}$ ⁠), the first uncountable ordinal.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Since a set cannot contain itself, ⁠ $\aleph _{1}$ ⁠ must have a strictly larger cardinality: ⁠ $\aleph _{0}<\aleph _{1}$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Furthermore, ⁠ $\aleph _{2}$ ⁠ is the set of all ordinals with cardinality less than or equal to ⁠ $\aleph _{1}$ ⁠, and in general the successor cardinal ⁠ $\kappa ^{+}$ ⁠is the set of all ordinals with cardinality up to ⁠ $\kappa$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Put another way for infinite cardinals, ⁠ $\kappa ^{+}$ ⁠ is the number of possible well-orderings on ⁠ $\kappa$ ⁠ up to order isomorphism.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Proving that such a set always exists is known as Hartogs' theorem, wherein the smallest ordinal not less or equal to than a set ⁠ $\kappa$ ⁠ is called the Hartogs number of ⁠ $\kappa$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Then, ⁠ $\aleph _{\lambda }$ ⁠ for a limit ordinal ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠ is the union of all lesser alephs.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The importance of ordinal numbers here is to generalize the notion of counting to infinite sets.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] When counting, one implicitly assigns an order to their set of objects, but no matter what order one assigns the final result of the count is always the same, which demonstrates the connection between cardinal and ordinal numbers.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Further, by the well-ordering theorem, there cannot exist any set with cardinality between ⁠ $\aleph _{0}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\aleph _{1}$ ⁠, and every infinite set has some cardinality corresponding uniquely to some aleph ⁠ $\aleph _{\alpha }$ ⁠, for some ordinal ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] This allows one to use a constructive definition of the cardinality function, by assigning each set to its equinumerous aleph.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Basic arithmetic can be done on cardinal numbers in a very natural way, by extending the theorems for finite combinatorial principles above.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The intuitive principle that if ⁠ A ⁠ and ⁠ B ⁠ are disjoint then addition of these sets is simply taking their union, written as ⁠ $\vert A\cup B\vert =\vert A\vert +\vert B\vert$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Thus if ⁠ A ⁠ and ⁠ B ⁠ are infinite, cardinal addition is defined as ⁠ ${\displaystyle \vert A\vert +\vert B\vert$ ⁠ where ⁠ $\sqcup$ ⁠ denotes disjoint union.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Similarly, the multiplication of two sets is intuitively the number of ways to pair their elements (as in the multiplication principle), therefore cardinal multiplication is defined as ⁠ ${\displaystyle \vert A\vert \cdot \vert B\vert$ ⁠, where ⁠ $\times$ ⁠ denotes the Cartesian product.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Although a lot of properties of finite arithmetic hold for infinite arithmetic, as above and in the table below, strict inequalities (such as Kőnig's theorem) are rare.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] For example, in finite arithmetic, for any nonzero number ⁠ n ⁠, ⁠ $n+n>n$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] However, since both the set of even numbers ⁠ $(E)$ ⁠ and set of odd numbers ⁠ $(F)$ ⁠ have cardinality ⁠ $\aleph _{0}$ ⁠, it shows ⁠ $\vert E\sqcup F\vert =\vert \mathbb {N} \vert$ ⁠ thus ⁠ $\aleph _{0}+\aleph _{0}=\aleph _{0}$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] In fact, for any infinite cardinal, ⁠ $\kappa +\kappa =\kappa \cdot \kappa =\kappa$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] In this way, infinite cardinal addition and multiplication are considered to be remarkably well-behaved (at least under the Axiom of Choice).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Cardinal exponentiation ⁠ $\vert A\vert ^{\vert B\vert }$ ⁠ is defined via set exponentiation, the set of all functions ⁠ $f:B\mapsto A$ ⁠, that is, ⁠ $\vert A\vert ^{\vert B\vert }:=\vert A^{B}\vert$ ⁠ which naturally extends the role of "repeated multiplication" to infinite sets.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] For finite sets this can be shown to coincide with standard natural number exponentiation, but includes as a corollary that zero to the power of zero is one ⁠ $(0^{0}=1)$ ⁠ since there is exactly one function from the empty set to itself: the empty function.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] A combinatorial argument can be used to show ⁠ $2^{\vert A\vert }=\vert {\mathcal {P}}(A)\vert$ ⁠, by considering the indicator function of each subset.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] In general, cardinal exponentiation is not as well-behaved as addition and multiplication.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] For example, even though it can be proven that the expression ⁠ $2^{\aleph _{0}}$ ⁠does indeed correspond to some aleph, it is unprovable from standard set theories which aleph it corresponds to.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The *set of all cardinal numbers* refers to a hypothetical set which contains all cardinal numbers.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Such a set cannot exist, which has been considered paradoxical, and related to the Burali-Forti paradox.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Using the definition of cardinal numbers as representatives of their cardinalities.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] It begins by assuming there is some set ⁠ $S:=\{X\,\vert X{\text{ is a cardinal number}}\}$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Then, if there is some largest cardinal ⁠ $\kappa \in S$ ⁠, then the powerset ⁠ $2^{\kappa }$ ⁠ is strictly greater, and thus not in ⁠ S ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Conversely, if there is no largest element, then the union ⁠ $\bigcup S$ ⁠ contains the elements of all elements of ⁠ S ⁠, and is therefore greater than or equal to each element.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Since there is no largest element in ⁠ S ⁠, for any element ⁠ $x\in S$ ⁠, there is another element ⁠ $y\in S$ ⁠ such that ⁠ $\vert x\vert <\vert y\vert$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\vert y\vert \leq {\Bigl \vert }\bigcup S{\Bigr \vert }$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Thus, for any ⁠ $x\in S$ ⁠, ⁠ $\vert x\vert <{\Bigl \vert }\bigcup S{\Bigr \vert }$ ⁠, and so ⁠ ${\Bigl \vert }\bigcup S{\Bigr \vert }\notin S$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Thus, the collection of all cardinal numbers is too large to form a set, and is a proper class.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Georg Cantor denoted the collection of all cardinal numbers **ת‎** (tav, the last letter of the Hebrew alphabet), and considered it to be an "inconsistent multiplicity".
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The real numbers ⁠ $(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠ formalize the intuitive notion of the *continuum*: the unbroken, gapless set of points on the number line.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] There are numerous ways to construct and analyze the continuum in set theory, for example, sets of Cauchy sequences of rational numbers, or Dedekind cuts.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] However, a somewhat informal definition as the set of infinite sequences of digits, e.g. ⁠ $0.1234...$ ⁠, with the usual arithmetic and order is a popular and sufficient choice for basic arguments involving the continuum.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The cardinality of this set, denoted "⁠ ${\mathfrak {c}}$ ⁠" (a lowercase fraktur script "c"), turns out to be remarkably stable under various transformations.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] For example, all intervals on the real line e.g. ⁠ $[0,1]$ ⁠, and ⁠ $[0,2]$ ⁠, have the same cardinality as the entire set ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The fact that two intervals of unequal length can be mapped one-to-one has been known, even if considered paradoxical, for thousands of years (cf.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Further, the tangent function is a bijection from the interval ⁠ $\textstyle \left({\frac {-\pi }{2}}\,,{\frac {\pi }{2}}\right)$ ⁠ to the whole real line.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] A more surprising example is the Cantor set, which is defined as follows: take the interval ⁠ $[0,1]$ ⁠ and remove the middle third ⁠ $\textstyle ({\frac {1}{3}},{\frac {2}{3}})$ ⁠, then remove the middle third of each of the two remaining segments, and continue removing middle thirds (see image).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The Cantor set is the collection of points that survive this process.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The remaining points are exactly those whose decimal expansion can be written in ternary without a 1.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Reinterpreting these decimal expansions as binary (e.g. by replacing the 2s with 1s) gives a bijection between the Cantor set and the interval ⁠ $[0,1]$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The Cantor set has a measure or "length" of zero, and yet is still equinumerous to the whole real line.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] In the other direction, into higher dimensions, one can find a bijective map between a one-dimensional line and a two-dimensional square.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Space-filling curves offer a more visual proof, giving a continuous map from the unit interval onto the unit square.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Classical examples include the Peano curve and Hilbert curve.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Although these maps are not bijective, they are indeed sufficient to show ⁠ $\vert \mathbb {R} ^{2}\vert \leq \vert \mathbb {R} \vert$ ⁠ with the converse being immediate.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Both of these methods can be reused at each dimension to show that ⁠ $\vert \mathbb {R} ^{n}\vert =\vert \mathbb {R} ^{n+1}\vert$ ⁠ and thus ⁠ $\vert \mathbb {R} \vert =\vert \mathbb {R} ^{n}\vert$ ⁠ for any dimension ⁠ $n\geq 1$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Thus, the real numbers, all finite-dimensional real spaces, and the countable cartesian product have the same cardinality.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] As shown in § Uncountable sets, the set of real numbers is strictly larger than the set of natural numbers.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The Continuum Hypothesis (CH) asserts that the real numbers have the next largest cardinality after the natural numbers, that is ⁠ $\vert \mathbb {R} \vert =\aleph _{1}$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] As shown by Gödel and Cohen, the continuum hypothesis is independent of ZFC, a standard axiomatization of set theory; that is, it is impossible to prove the continuum hypothesis or its negation from ZFC—provided that ZFC is consistent, meaning it produces no contradictions.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] The Generalized Continuum Hypothesis (GCH) extends this to all infinite cardinals, stating that ⁠ $2^{\aleph _{\alpha }}=\aleph _{\alpha +1}$ ⁠ for every ordinal ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Research on CH and GCH continues independent of ZFC, especially in descriptive set theory and through the exploration of large cardinal axioms.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p01] Without GCH, the cardinality of ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠ cannot be written in terms of specific alephs.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Around the turn of the 20th century, set theory turned to an axiomatic approach to avoid rampant foundational issues related to its naive study (cf.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] The most common axiomatic set theory used today is Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory (ZFC).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] ZFC has been criticized both for being too strong, and too weak.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Similarly, there are many "natural extensions" of ZFC studied by set theorists.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Thus, there exist many alternative systems of axioms each of which has implications to the standard theory of cardinality discussed above.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] The Axiom of Choice (AC) is a fundamental principle in the foundations of mathematics which has seen much controversy in its history.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Informally, it states that given any collection of non-empty sets, it is possible to construct a new set by choosing one element from each set, even if the collection is infinite.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] The controversy over AC had mostly to do with the nature of how it chose these elements.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Whereas most axioms seem to describe what sets are or allow one to construct explicit sets, AC does not tell you *which* set you have constructed, just that such a choice function exists, leaving the constructed set implicit.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] It is hardly controversial to modern mathematicians.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] However, because of its unique historical controversy it is often given special treatment not given to other axioms that basic proofs which use it ought to call it out.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] The Axiom of Choice is very closely related to the nature of cardinality.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] AC imposes a strict structure on what cardinality can be and what it means to compare to sets.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Assuming AC is false, cardinality has a much more intricate structure and resists the kind of linear order AC offers.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] For example, cardinal inequality does not treat injection and surjection equivalently.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Specifically, there exists sets, such that there is a surjection from ⁠ A ⁠ onto ⁠ B ⁠, but no injection from ⁠ B ⁠ into ⁠ A ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Thus injection is a strictly stronger notion, since, given an injection, it is always possible to find a surjection in the opposite direction.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Similarly, although cardinal inequality maintains a partial order, there exist incomparable sets under cardinal inequality, that is, the law of trichotomy fails to hold, and there are sets such that none of ⁠ $A<B$ ⁠, ⁠ $A\sim B$ ⁠, ⁠ $A>B$ ⁠ hold.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Both of these (trichotomy and that surjection implies injection) are equivalent to AC.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Because trichotomy does not hold and the aleph sequence has a natural well-order, there exist sets whose cardinality does not correspond to any aleph.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] As such, the cardinality function ⁠ $A\mapsto \vert A\vert$ ⁠ becomes somewhat more difficult to define.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] In fact, a cardinality function that maps each set to a unique "representative" of that cardinality—i.e. satisfying Hume's principle, and idempotence (⁠ $\vert \vert S\vert \vert =\vert S\vert$ ⁠ or ⁠ $\vert S\vert \sim S$ ⁠)—is impossible without AC.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Set theories without AC address this by adopting the so-called *Frege–Russell–Scott* definition, introduced by Dana Scott, reminiscent of the *Frege–Russell* cardinal numbers.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Under this definition, one considers the "Set of all sets" equinumerous with ⁠ A ⁠, but applies Scott's trick to regularize these classes.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Specifically, it reduces this class to only those sets of minimal rank; that is, those sets which appear earliest in the von Neumann hierarchy.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Since the von Neumann hierarchy is well-ordered, there is a least rank, and since these sets all share that rank, their collection is bounded in the hierarchy and thus constitutes a set rather than a proper class.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Cardinal arithmetic is much more involved, losing many of its simplest identities.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] The identity ⁠ $\vert A\vert +\vert B\vert =\operatorname {max} (\vert A\vert ,\vert B\vert )$ ⁠ requires a well-defined notion of "max" which requires all sets to be comparable, and therefore does not hold.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Similarly, the statement that ⁠ ${\mathfrak {p}}^{2}={\mathfrak {p}}$ ⁠ for every infinite cardinal ⁠ ${\mathfrak {p}}$ ⁠, and even the statement that the arbitrary product of non-zero cardinal numbers always non-zero—called the *Multiplicative axiom* by Bertrand Russell—are both equivalent to AC.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Further, although the Generalized Continuum Hypothesis (GCH, that ⁠ $\aleph _{\alpha }=\beth _{\alpha }$ ⁠ for every ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠) is independent of ZFC, it can be shown ZF+GCH is sufficient to derive AC, and therefore, if AC is false, it follows that GCH does not hold.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Some set theories include classes, which are collections of sets, which allows theories to discuss any collection of sets without running into issues self-reference (e.g. the set of all sets that do not contain themselves.).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] A class is called a proper class when, at least intuitively, it is "too large" to form a set.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] For example, the universe of all sets, the class of all cardinal numbers, and the class of all ordinal numbers are proper classes.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Such set theories include Von Neumann–Bernays–Gödel set theory (NBG), and Morse–Kelley set theory (MK).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Cantor originally called the size of these "too large" sets "absolute infinite", separating it from the transfinite.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] The former he characterized by its "inconsistency", causing paradoxes, and associated the concept with God.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Proper classes can, in a sense, be assigned cardinalities.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] The first to formally distinguish between sets and classes was John von Neumann, who formalized the notion of "too large to form sets".
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] More accurately, he defined a class to be "too big" (a proper class) if and only if it was equinumerous with the whole universe of sets (cf.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] *Axiom of limitation of size*; used as an axiom in MK set theory, and derivable as a theorem in NBG).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Thus, all proper classes have the same "size".
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] The axiom has several implications, mostly relating to the limitation of size principles of early set theory.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] It implies the axiom of specification, the axiom of replacement, the axiom of union, and the axiom of global choice.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Large cardinal axioms assert the existence of cardinal numbers which, as the name suggests, are very large—so large that they cannot be proven to exist within ZFC.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] For example, an inaccessible cardinal is, roughly, a cardinal that cannot be approached from below using basic set-theoretic operations such as unions, limits, and powersets (more formally, a regular, limit cardinal greater than ⁠ $\aleph _{0}$ ⁠).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Large cardinals are understood in terms of the Von Neumann hierarchy, denoted ⁠ $V_{\alpha }$ ⁠ (for some ordinal ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠), which can be understood as the sets that can be obtained from the empty set, followed by recursively applying the powerset ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠ times.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] There exist many known properties defining large cardinals, which come seemingly in a linear hierarchy, in terms of consistency strength.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] As an analogy, in ZFC without the Axiom of Infinity can only prove the existence of finite sets.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Therefore ⁠ $V_{\omega }(={\mathcal {P}}(\varnothing )\cup {\mathcal {P}}({\mathcal {P}}(\varnothing ))\cup \cdots )$ ⁠, whose existence is provable in usual ZFC, can serve as a model of ZFC–Infinity, and thus if ZFC is consistent, ZFC–Infinity is consistent.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Analogously, ZFC+"There exists an inaccessible cardinal" implies the consistency of ZFC, since if ⁠ $\kappa$ ⁠ is inaccessible, ⁠ $V_{\kappa }$ ⁠ can serve as a model of ZFC (cf.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Stronger and stronger large cardinal axioms assert the existence of larger and larger cardinals, each of which proves the consistency of the weaker systems.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Large cardinals are at the forefront of set-theoretic research for both practical and philosophical reasons.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] In a practical sense, it is often the case that unproven or unprovable conjectures can be settled by sufficiently strong large cardinal axioms.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] For example, the existence of a measurable cardinal is inconsistent with Gödel's constructibility axiom.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Similarly, the existence of a Reinhardt cardinal is inconsistent with the axiom of choice, which makes it a much more controversial large cardinal axiom.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] In a philosophical sense, according to a platonic view among set-theorists such as W.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Hugh Woodin, these axioms simply extend the system to include sets that are "supposed" to be considered.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] That is, there is some fundamental universe of sets, which these axioms grant further access to.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] For this reason, large cardinal axioms are generally given preference compared to other possible axioms of set theory.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] This view is controversial among a competing philosophy, sometimes called pluralism, which posits that set theory should be understood as a multiverse of set theories, but no "absolute" or "true" model.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] The Axiom of Determinacy (AD) asserts that certain kinds of mathematical games on the natural numbers are determined; that is, one player will always have a guaranteed winning strategy.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] The first serious study of the consequences of AD started during the 1960s in descriptive set theory—which, roughly, studies the definable sets of the real numbers—after it was noticed that it leads to very nice regulatory properties of the real numbers.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] However, it was shown that this axiom is inconsistent with AC and thus was never taken as a fundamental axiom of set theory.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] AD is closely related to the cardinality of the real numbers, giving it a structure different from that under AC.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Under AD, the real numbers cannot be well-ordered, meaning ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠ does not correspond to any aleph.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Despite this, AD imposes a rigid structure on the real numbers, known as the perfect set property, implying that every set of real numbers is either countable, or has cardinality of exactly ⁠ $2^{\aleph _{0}}$ ⁠, equal to the whole real line.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Similarly, it also implies that all sets of real numbers are Lebesgue measurable, eliminating the existence of sets whose size is non-zero, but cannot be assigned a length.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Existence of such non-measurable sets allows the Banach–Tarski paradox, demonstrating that one can cut one sphere into finitely many pieces, smoothly rearrange them, and end with two solid spheres, which becomes impossible under AD.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] On the other hand, due to the restrictions on what sets can exist, it implies that one can partition the real numbers into *strictly* more groups than there are real numbers.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Specifically, one can find an injection to show that ⁠ $\vert \mathbb {R} \vert \leq \vert \mathbb {R} /\mathbb {Q} \vert$ ⁠ (equivalence classes of reals, such that ⁠ $x\sim y$ ⁠ iff ⁠ $x-y\in \mathbb {Q}$ ⁠).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] However, if an injection ⁠ $F:\mathbb {R} /\mathbb {Q} \to \mathbb {R}$ ⁠ existed, then there is a linear order on ⁠ $\mathbb {R} /\mathbb {Q}$ ⁠ (given by ⁠ $a\leq b$ ⁠ if ⁠ $F(a)\leq F(b)$ ⁠).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] This allows one to construct a set which cannot be assigned a measure, contradicting AD.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Therefore no such injection could exist, and thus ⁠ $\vert \mathbb {R} \vert <\vert \mathbb {R} /\mathbb {Q} \vert$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] However, its relationship with large cardinals and the continuum hypothesis is still of heavy interest among set theorists such as Donald A.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Hugh Woodin, at least in part because AD is equiconsistent with the large cardinal axiom that there exists infinitely many Woodin cardinals.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] In model theory, a model corresponds to a specific interpretation of a formal language or theory.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] It consists of a domain (a set of objects) and an interpretation of the symbols in the language, such that the axioms of the theory are satisfied within this structure.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] In first-order logic, the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem states that if a countable theory has an infinite model, then it also has models of every other infinite cardinality.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Applied to set theory, it asserts that Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory, which proves the existence of uncountable sets such as ⁠ ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ ⁠, nevertheless has a countable model.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Thus, Skolem's paradox was posed as follows: how can it be that there exists a domain of set theory which only contains countably many objects, but is capable of satisfying the statement "there exists a set with uncountably many elements"?
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Skolem's paradox does not only apply to ZFC, but *any* first-order set theory, if it is countable and consistent, has a model which is countable.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] A mathematical explanation of the paradox, showing that it is not a true contradiction in mathematics, was first given in 1922 by Thoralf Skolem, who asserted it as a reason against founding mathematics on first order logic.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] He explained that the countability or uncountability of a set is not absolute, but relative to the model in which the cardinality is measured.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] This is because, for example, if the set ⁠ X ⁠ is countable in a model of set theory then there is a bijection ⁠ $f:\mathbb {N} \mapsto X$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] But a submodel containing ⁠ X ⁠ which excludes all such functions would thus contain no bijection between ⁠ X ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbb {N}$ ⁠, and therefore ⁠ X ⁠ would be uncountable.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] In second-order and higher-order logics, the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem does not hold.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] This is due to the fact that second-order logic quantifies over all subsets of the domain.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Skolem's work was harshly received by Ernst Zermelo, who argued against the limitations of first-order logic and Skolem's notion of "relativity", but the result quickly came to be accepted by the mathematical community.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] From the 6th century BCE, the writings of Greek philosophers, such as Anaximander, discussed infinite sets or objects, however, those objects were generally viewed as paradoxical and imperfect (cf.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] This was codified in Euclid's *Elements*, where the fifth common notion stated "The whole is greater than the part", called the *Euclidean principle*.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] This principle was the dominating philosophy in mathematics until the 19th century.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Around the 4th century BCE, Jaina mathematics were the first to discuss different sizes of infinity.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] They defined three major classes of number: enumerable (finite numbers), unenumerable (*asamkhyata*, roughly, countably infinite), and infinite (*ananta*, roughly, the continuum).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Then they had five classes of infinite numbers: infinite in one direction, infinite in both directions, infinite in area, infinite everywhere, and infinite perpetually.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] One of the earliest explicit uses of a one-to-one correspondence is recorded in Aristotle's *Mechanics* (c.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] 350 BCE), known as Aristotle's wheel paradox.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] The paradox can be briefly described as follows: A wheel is depicted as two concentric circles.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] The larger, outer circle is tangent to a horizontal line (e.g. a road that it rolls on), while the smaller, inner circle is rigidly affixed to the larger.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Assuming the larger circle rolls along the line without slipping (or skidding) for one full revolution, the distances moved by both circles are the same: the circumference of the larger circle.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Further, the lines traced by the bottom-most point of each is the same length.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Since the smaller wheel does not skip any points, and no point on the smaller wheel is used more than once, there is a one-to-one correspondence between the two circles.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Galileo Galilei presented what was later coined Galileo's paradox in his book *Two New Sciences* (1638), where he presented a seeming paradox in infinite sequences of numbers.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] It went as follows: for each perfect square ⁠ $(n^{2})$ ⁠ 1, 4, 9, 16, and so on, there is a unique square root ⁠ $\textstyle ({\sqrt {n^{2}}}=n)$ ⁠ 1, 2, 3, 4, and so on.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Therefore, there are as many perfect squares as there are square roots.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] However, every number is a square root, since it can be squared, but not every number is a perfect square.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Moreover, the proportion of perfect squares as one passes larger values diminishes, and is eventually smaller than any given fraction.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Galileo denied that this was fundamentally contradictory, however he concluded that this meant we could not compare the sizes of infinite sets, missing the opportunity to discover cardinality.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Bernard Bolzano's *Paradoxes of the Infinite* (*Paradoxien des Unendlichen*, 1851) is often considered the first systematic attempt to introduce the concept of sets into mathematical analysis.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] In this work, Bolzano defended the notion of actual infinity, presented an early formulation of what would later be recognized as one-to-one correspondence between infinite sets.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] He discussed examples such as the pairing between the intervals ⁠ $[0,5]$ ⁠ and ⁠ $[0,12]$ ⁠ by the relation ⁠ $5y=12x$ ⁠, and revisited Galileo's paradox.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] However, he too resisted saying that these sets were, in that sense, the same size.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] While *Paradoxes of the Infinite* anticipated several ideas central to later set theory, the work had little influence on contemporary mathematics, in part due to its posthumous publication and limited circulation.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] The concept of cardinality emerged nearly fully formed in the work of Georg Cantor during the 1870s and 1880s, in the context of mathematical analysis.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] In a series of papers beginning with *On a Property of the Collection of All Real Algebraic Numbers* (1874), Cantor introduced the idea of comparing the sizes of infinite sets, through the notion of one-to-one correspondence.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] He showed that the set of real numbers was, in this sense, strictly larger than the set of natural numbers using a nested intervals argument.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] This result was later refined into the more widely known diagonal argument in 1891, published in *Über eine elementare Frage der Mannigfaltigkeitslehre,* where he also proved the more general result (now called Cantor's Theorem) that the power set of any set is strictly larger than the set itself.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Cantor introduced the notion cardinal numbers together with ordinal numbers, which he viewed as abstractions of sets.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] For a given set ⁠ M ⁠, he wrote ⁠ $\textstyle {\overline {M}}$ ⁠ to mean the abstraction of that set from its elements, while maintaining their order, and cardinal numbers were a double abstraction, written ⁠ $\textstyle M$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] He also introduced the Aleph sequence for infinite cardinal numbers.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] These notations appeared in correspondence and were formalized in his later writings, particularly the series *Beiträge zur Begründung der transfiniten Mengenlehre* (1895–1897).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] In these works, Cantor developed an arithmetic of cardinal numbers, defining addition, multiplication, and exponentiation of cardinal numbers.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] This led to the formulation of the Continuum Hypothesis: whether ⁠ $2^{\aleph _{0}}=\aleph _{1}$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Cantor was unable to resolve CH and left it as an open problem.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Parallel to Cantor’s development, Richard Dedekind independently formulated many advanced theorems of set theory, and helped establish set-theoretic foundations of algebra and arithmetic.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Dedekind's *The Nature and Meaning of Numbers* (1888) emphasized structural properties over extensional definitions, and supported the bijective formulation of size and number.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Dedekind was in correspondence with Cantor during the development of set theory; he supplied Cantor with a proof of the countability of the algebraic numbers, and gave feedback and modifications on Cantor's proofs before publishing.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] After Cantor's 1883 proof that all finite-dimensional spaces ⁠ $(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ⁠ have the same cardinality, in 1890, Giuseppe Peano introduced the Peano curve, which was a more visual proof that the unit interval ⁠ $[0,1]$ ⁠ has the same cardinality as the unit square on ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ ⁠.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] This created a new area of mathematical analysis studying what are now called space-filling curves.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] In 1894, attempting to formalize Cantor's "cardinal number", Peano introduced "definition by abstraction": if one can define an equivalence relation, then one may define "that property" which an equivalence class describes.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] However, this was received harshly by Russell for not considering that this property may not be unique.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] German logician Gottlob Frege attempted to ground the concepts of number and arithmetic in logic using Cantor's theory of cardinality and Hume's principle in *Die Grundlagen der Arithmetik* (1884) and the subsequent *Grundgesetze der Arithmetik* (1893, 1903).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Frege defined cardinal numbers as equivalence classes of sets under equinumerosity.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] However, Frege's approach to set theory was later shown to be flawed.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] His approach was eventually reformalized by Bertrand Russell and Alfred Whitehead in *Principia Mathematica* (1910–1913, vol.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] This definition of cardinal numbers is now referred to as the *Frege–Russell* definition.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] This definition was eventually superseded by the convention established by John von Neumann in 1928 which uses representatives to define cardinal numbers.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] At the Paris conference of the International Congress of Mathematicians in 1900, David Hilbert, one of the most influential mathematicians of the time, gave a speech wherein he presented ten unsolved problems (of a total of 23, later published, now called *Hilbert's problems*).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Of these, he placed "Cantor's problem" (now called the Continuum Hypothesis) as the first on the list.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] This list of problems would prove to be very influential in 20th century mathematics, and attracted a lot of attention from other mathematicians toward Cantor's theory of cardinality.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Zermelo's system was extended by Abraham Fraenkel and Thoralf Skolem in the 1920s to create the standard foundation of set theory, called Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory (ZFC, "C" for the Axiom of Choice).
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] ZFC provided a rigorous foundation through which infinite cardinals could be systematically studied while avoiding the paradoxes of naive set theory.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Ignoring possible foundational issues, during the early 1900s, Felix Hausdorff began studying "exorbitant numbers": roughly, very large cardinal numbers, or what are now called inaccessible cardinals.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] This work was continued and popularized by several other influential set theorists such as Paul Mahlo—who introduced Mahlo cardinals—as well as Wacław Sierpiński, and Alfred Tarski.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Their work would eventually be known collectively as the study of large cardinals.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Inaccessible cardinals were used as Grothendieck universes in category theory as an optional organizational tool to treat certain large categories as sets instead of proper classes.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] In 1940, Kurt Gödel showed that the Continuum Hypothesis (CH) cannot be *disproved* from the axioms of ZFC by showing that both CH and AC hold in his constructible universe: an inner model of ZFC.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] The existence of a model of ZFC in which additional axioms hold shows that the additional axioms are (relatively) consistent with ZFC.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] In 1963, Paul Cohen showed that CH cannot be *proven* from the ZFC axioms, which showed that CH was independent from ZFC.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] To prove his result, Cohen developed the method of forcing, which has become a standard tool in set theory.
[src:metrics-cardinality/cardinality-p02] Cohen was awarded the Fields Medal in 1966 for his proof.
[src:metrics-cardinality/concepts-data-model] Prometheus fundamentally stores all data as *time series*: streams of timestamped values belonging to the same metric and the same set of labeled dimensions.
[src:metrics-cardinality/concepts-data-model] Besides stored time series, Prometheus may generate temporary derived time series as the result of queries.
[src:metrics-cardinality/concepts-data-model] Every time series is uniquely identified by its metric name and optional key-value pairs called labels.
[src:metrics-cardinality/concepts-data-model] Labels let you capture different instances of the same metric name.
[src:metrics-cardinality/concepts-data-model] For example: all HTTP requests that used the method `POST` to the `/api/tracks` handler.
[src:metrics-cardinality/concepts-data-model] We refer to this as Prometheus's "dimensional data model".
[src:metrics-cardinality/concepts-data-model] The query language allows filtering and aggregation based on these dimensions.
[src:metrics-cardinality/concepts-data-model] The change of any label's value, including adding or removing labels, will create a new time series.
[src:metrics-cardinality/concepts-data-model] WARNING: The UTF-8 support for metric and label names was added relatively recently in Prometheus v3.0.0.
[src:metrics-cardinality/concepts-data-model] It might take time for the wider ecosystem (downstream PromQL compatible projects and vendors, tooling, third-party instrumentation, collectors, etc.) to adopt new quoting mechanisms, relaxed validation etc.
[src:metrics-cardinality/concepts-data-model] For the best compatibility it's recommended to stick to the recommended ("SHOULD") character set.
[src:metrics-cardinality/concepts-data-model] INFO: See also the best practices for naming metrics and labels.
[src:metrics-cardinality/concepts-data-model] Samples form the actual time series data.
[src:metrics-cardinality/concepts-data-model] This is the same notation that OpenTSDB uses.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] A **dimension** is a structure that categorizes facts and measures in order to enable users to answer business questions.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Commonly used dimensions are people, products, place and time.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] In a data warehouse, dimensions provide structured labeling information to otherwise unordered numeric measures.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] The dimension is a data set composed of individual, non-overlapping data elements.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] The primary functions of dimensions are threefold: to provide filtering, grouping and labelling.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] These functions are often described as "slice and dice".
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] A common data warehouse example involves sales as the measure, with customer and product as dimensions.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] The data can be sliced by removing all customers except for a group under study, and then diced by grouping by product.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] A dimensional data element is similar to a categorical variable in statistics.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Typically dimensions in a data warehouse are organized internally into one or more hierarchies.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] A slowly changing dimension is a set of data attributes that change slowly over a period of time rather than changing regularly e.g. address or name.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] These attributes can change over a period of time and that will get combined as a slowly changing dimension.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] A conformed dimension is a set of data attributes that have been physically referenced in multiple database tables using the same key value to refer to the same structure, attributes, domain values, definitions and concepts.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] A conformed dimension cuts across many facts.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Dimensions are conformed when they are either exactly the same (including keys) or one is a proper subset of the other.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Conformed dimensions are either identical or strict mathematical subsets of the most granular, detailed dimension.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Dimension tables are not conformed if the attributes are labeled differently or contain different values.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Conformed dimensions come in several different flavors.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] At the most basic level, conformed dimensions mean exactly the same thing with every possible fact table to which they are joined.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] The date dimension table connected to the sales facts is identical to the date dimension connected to the inventory facts.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] A junk dimension is a convenient grouping of typically low-cardinality flags and indicators.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] By creating an abstract dimension, these flags and indicators are removed from the fact table while placing them into a useful dimensional framework.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] A junk dimension is a dimension table consisting of attributes that do not belong in the fact table or in any of the existing dimension tables.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] The nature of these attributes is usually text or various flags, e.g. non-generic comments or just simple yes/no or true/false indicators.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] These kinds of attributes are typically remaining when all the obvious dimensions in the business process have been identified and thus the designer is faced with the challenge of where to put these attributes that do not belong in the other dimensions.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] One solution is to create a new dimension for each of the remaining attributes, but due to their nature, it could be necessary to create a vast number of new dimensions resulting in a fact table with a very large number of foreign keys.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] The designer could also decide to leave the remaining attributes in the fact table but this could make the row length of the table unnecessarily large if, for example, the attribute is a long text string.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] The solution to this challenge is to identify all the attributes and then put them into one or several junk dimensions.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] One junk dimension can hold several true/false or yes/no indicators that have no correlation with each other, so it would be convenient to convert the indicators into a more describing attribute.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] An example would be an indicator about whether a package had arrived: instead of indicating this as “yes” or “no”, it would be converted into "arrived" or "pending" in the junk dimension.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] The designer can choose to build the dimension table so it ends up holding all the indicators occurring with every other indicator so that all combinations are covered.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] This sets up a fixed size for the table itself which would be 2*x* rows, where *x* is the number of indicators.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] This solution is appropriate in situations where the designer would expect to encounter a lot of different combinations and where the possible combinations are limited to an acceptable level.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] In a situation where the number of indicators are large, thus creating a very big table or where the designer only expects to encounter a few of the possible combinations, it would be more appropriate to build each row in the junk dimension as new combinations are encountered.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] To limit the size of the tables, multiple junk dimensions might be appropriate in other situations depending on the correlation between various indicators.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Junk dimensions are also appropriate for placing attributes like non-generic comments from the fact table.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Such attributes might consist of data from an optional comment field when a customer places an order and as a result will probably be blank in many cases.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Therefore, the junk dimension should contain a single row representing the blanks as a surrogate key that will be used in the fact table for every row returned with a blank comment field.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] A degenerate dimension is a key, such as a transaction number, invoice number, ticket number, or bill-of-lading number, that has no attributes and hence does not join to an actual dimension table.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Degenerate dimensions are very common when the grain of a fact table represents a single transaction item or line item because the degenerate dimension represents the unique identifier of the parent.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Degenerate dimensions often play an integral role in the fact table's primary key.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Dimensions are often recycled for multiple applications within the same database.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] For instance, a "Date" dimension can be used for "Date of Sale", as well as "Date of Delivery", or "Date of Hire".
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] This is often referred to as a "role-playing dimension".
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] This can be implemented using a view over the same dimension table.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Usually dimension tables do not reference other dimensions via foreign keys.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] When this happens, the referenced dimension is called an outrigger dimension.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Outrigger dimensions should be considered a data warehouse anti-pattern: it is considered a better practice to use some fact tables that relate the two dimensions.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] A conformed dimensions is said to be a shrunken dimension when it includes a subset of the rows and/or columns of the original dimension.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] A special type of dimension can be used to represent dates with a granularity of a day.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Dates would be referenced in a fact table as foreign keys to a date dimension.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] The date dimension primary key could be a surrogate key or a number using the format YYYYMMDD.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] The date dimension can include other attributes like the week of the year, or flags representing work days, holidays, etc.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] It could also include special rows representing: not known dates, or yet to be defined dates.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] The date dimension should be initialized with all the required dates, say the next 10 years of dates, or more if required, or past dates if events in the past are handled.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Time instead is usually best represented as a timestamp in the fact table.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] When referencing data from a metadata registry such as ISO/IEC 11179, representation terms such as "Indicator" (a Boolean true/false value), "Code" (a set of non-overlapping enumerated values) are typically used as dimensions.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] For example, using the National Information Exchange Model (NIEM) the data element name would be "PersonGenderCode" and the enumerated values might be "male", "female" and "unknown".
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] In data warehousing, a dimension table is one of the set of companion tables to a fact table.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] The fact table contains business facts (or measures), and foreign keys which refer to candidate keys (normally primary keys) in the dimension tables.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Contrary to fact tables, dimension tables contain descriptive attributes (or fields) that are typically textual fields (or discrete numbers that behave like text).
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] These attributes are designed to serve two critical purposes: query constraining and/or filtering, and query result set labeling.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Dimension table rows are uniquely identified by a single key field.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] It is recommended that the key field be a simple integer because a key value is meaningless, used only for joining fields between the fact and dimension tables.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Dimension tables often use primary keys that are also surrogate keys.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Surrogate keys are often auto-generated (e.g. a Sybase or SQL Server "identity column", a PostgreSQL or Informix serial, an Oracle SEQUENCE or a column defined with AUTO_INCREMENT in MySQL).
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Although surrogate key use places a burden on the ETL system, pipeline processing can be improved, and ETL tools have built-in improved surrogate key processing.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] The goal of a dimension table is to create standardized, conformed dimensions that can be shared across the enterprise's data warehouse environment, and enable joining to multiple fact tables representing various business processes.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Over time, the attributes of a given row in a dimension table may change.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] For example, the shipping address for a company may change.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Kimball refers to this phenomenon as slowly changing dimension.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Since many fact tables in a data warehouse are time series of observations, one or more date dimensions are often needed.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] One of the reasons to have date dimensions is to place calendar knowledge in the data warehouse instead of hard-coded in an application.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] While a simple SQL date-timestamp is useful for providing accurate information about the time a fact was recorded, it can not give information about holidays, fiscal periods, etc.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] An SQL date-timestamp can still be useful to store in the fact table, as it allows for precise calculations.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Having both the date and time of day in the same dimension, may easily result in a huge dimension with millions of rows.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] If a high amount of detail is needed it is usually a good idea to split date and time into two or more separate dimensions.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] A time dimension with a grain of seconds in a day will only have 86400 rows.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] A more or less detailed grain for date/time dimensions can be chosen depending on needs.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] As examples, date dimensions can be accurate to year, quarter, month or day and time dimensions can be accurate to hours, minutes or seconds.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] As a rule of thumb, time of day dimension should only be created if hierarchical groupings are needed or if there are meaningful textual descriptions for periods of time within the day (ex. “evening rush” or “first shift”).
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] If the rows in a fact table are coming from several time zones, it might be useful to store date and time in both local time and a standard time.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] This can be done by having two dimensions for each date/time dimension needed – one for local time, and one for standard time.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] Storing date/time in both local and standard time, will allow for analysis on when facts are created in a local setting and in a global setting as well.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] The standard time chosen can be a global standard time (ex.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] UTC), it can be the local time of the business’ headquarters (ex.
[src:metrics-cardinality/dimension-data-warehouse] CET), or any other time zone that would make sense to use.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] In mathematics, a **metric space** is a set together with a notion of distance between its points.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The distance is measured by a function called a **metric** or **distance function**.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Metric spaces are a general setting for studying many of the concepts of mathematical analysis and geometry.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The most familiar example of a metric space is 3-dimensional Euclidean space with its usual notion of distance.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Other well-known examples are a sphere equipped with the angular distance and the hyperbolic plane.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] A metric may correspond to a metaphorical, rather than physical, notion of distance.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, the set of 100-character Unicode strings can be equipped with the Hamming distance, which measures the number of characters that need to be changed to get from one string to another.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Metric spaces appear in many different branches of mathematics.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, Riemannian manifolds, normed vector spaces, and graphs may be viewed as metric spaces.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] In abstract algebra, the field of *p*-adic numbers is the completion of the field of rational numbers with respect to a certain metric.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Metric spaces are also studied in their own right in **metric geometry** and **analysis on metric spaces**.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Many notions of analysis, including balls, completeness, as well as uniform, Lipschitz, and Hölder continuity can be defined for metric spaces.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Other notions, such as continuity, compactness, and open and closed sets can be defined for metric spaces, but also in the even more general setting of topological spaces.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] To see the utility of different notions of distance, consider the surface of the Earth as a set of points.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] We can measure the distance between two such points by the length of the shortest path along the surface, "as the crow flies"; this is particularly useful for shipping and aviation.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] We can also measure the straight-line distance between two points through the Earth's interior; this notion is, for example, natural in seismology, since it roughly corresponds to the length of time it takes for seismic waves to travel between those two points.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The notion of distance encoded by the metric space axioms has relatively few requirements.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] This generality gives metric spaces a lot of flexibility.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] At the same time, the notion is strong enough to encode many intuitive facts about what distance means.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] This means that general results about metric spaces can be applied in many different contexts.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Like many fundamental mathematical concepts, the metric on a metric space can be interpreted in many different ways.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The triangle inequality holds: $d(x,z)\leq d(x,y)+d(y,z)$ This is a natural property of both physical and metaphorical notions of distance: you can arrive at z from x by taking a detour through y, but this will not make your journey any shorter than the direct path.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] It is traditional to write M as an abbreviation for (*M*, *d*) when it is understood what d is.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The real numbers with the distance function $d(x,y)=|y-x|$ given by the absolute difference form a metric space.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Many properties of metric spaces and functions between them are generalizations of concepts in real analysis and coincide with those concepts when applied to the real line.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The Euclidean plane $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ can be equipped with many different metrics.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The *taxicab* or *Manhattan* distance is defined by $d_{1}((x_{1},y_{1}),(x_{2},y_{2}))=|x_{2}-x_{1}|+|y_{2}-y_{1}|$ and can be thought of as the distance you need to travel along horizontal and vertical lines to get from one point to the other, as illustrated at the top of the article.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The *maximum*, $L^{\infty }$ , or *Chebyshev distance* is defined by $d_{\infty }((x_{1},y_{1}),(x_{2},y_{2}))=\max\{|x_{2}-x_{1}|,|y_{2}-y_{1}|\}.$ This distance does not have an easy explanation in terms of paths in the plane, but it still satisfies the metric space axioms.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] It can be thought of similarly to the number of moves a king would have to make on a chess board to travel from one point to another on the given space.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] In fact, these three distances, while they have distinct properties, are similar in some ways.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Informally, points that are close in one are close in the others, too.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] This observation can be quantified with the formula $d_{\infty }(p,q)\leq d_{2}(p,q)\leq d_{1}(p,q)\leq 2d_{\infty }(p,q),$ which holds for every pair of points $p,q\in \mathbb {R} ^{2}$ .
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Moreover, there exists a continuous family of distances $d_{\alpha }$ for $\alpha \in (1,\infty )$ that interpolates between these three distances.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] A radically different distance can be defined by setting $d(p,q)={\begin{cases}0,&{\text{if }}p=q,\\1,&{\text{otherwise.}}\end{cases}}$ In this *discrete metric*, all distinct points are 1 unit apart: none of them are close to each other, and none of them are very far away from each other either.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Intuitively, the discrete metric no longer remembers that the set is a plane, but treats it just as an undifferentiated set of points.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] All of these metrics can be easily extended to make sense on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ as well as $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ .
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Given a metric space (*M*, *d*) and a subset $A\subseteq M$ , we can consider A to be a metric space by measuring distances the same way we would in M.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Two more useful examples are the open interval (0, 1) and the closed interval [0, 1] thought of as subspaces of the real line.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Arthur Cayley, in his article "On Distance", extended metric concepts beyond Euclidean geometry into domains bounded by a conic in a projective space.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] His distance was given by logarithm of a cross ratio.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Any projectivity leaving the conic stable also leaves the cross ratio constant, so isometries are implicit.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] This method provides models for elliptic geometry and hyperbolic geometry, and Felix Klein, in several publications, established the field of non-euclidean geometry through the use of the Cayley-Klein metric.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The idea of an abstract space with metric properties was addressed in 1906 by René Maurice Fréchet and the term *metric space* was coined by Felix Hausdorff in 1914.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Fréchet's work laid the foundation for understanding convergence, continuity, and other key concepts in non-geometric spaces.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] This allowed mathematicians to study functions and sequences in a broader and more flexible way.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] This was important for the growing field of functional analysis.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Mathematicians like Hausdorff and Stefan Banach further refined and expanded the framework of metric spaces.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Hausdorff introduced topological spaces as a generalization of metric spaces.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Banach's work in functional analysis heavily relied on the metric structure.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Over time, metric spaces became a central part of modern mathematics.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] They have influenced various fields including topology, geometry, and applied mathematics.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Metric spaces continue to play a crucial role in the study of abstract mathematical concepts.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] A distance function is enough to define notions of closeness and convergence that were first developed in real analysis.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Properties that depend on the structure of a metric space are referred to as *metric properties*.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Every metric space is also a topological space, and some metric properties can also be rephrased without reference to distance in the language of topology; that is, they are really topological properties.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] For any point x in a metric space M and any real number *r* > 0, the *open ball* of radius r around x is defined to be the set of points that are strictly less than distance r from x: $B_{r}(x)=\{y\in M:d(x,y)<r\}.$ This is a natural way to define a set of points that are relatively close to x.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Therefore, a set $N\subseteq M$ is a *neighborhood* of x (informally, it contains all points "close enough" to x) if it contains an open ball of radius r around x for some *r* > 0.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] An *open set* is a set which is a neighborhood of all its points.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] It follows that the open balls form a base for a topology on M.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] In other words, the open sets of M are exactly the unions of open balls.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] As in any topology, closed sets are the complements of open sets.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Sets may be both open and closed as well as neither open nor closed.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] This topology does not carry all the information about the metric space.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, the distances *d*1, *d*2, and *d*∞ defined above all induce the same topology on $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ , although they behave differently in many respects.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Similarly, $\mathbb {R}$ with the Euclidean metric and its subspace the interval (0, 1) with the induced metric are homeomorphic but have very different metric properties.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Conversely, not every topological space can be given a metric.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Topological spaces which are compatible with a metric are called *metrizable* and are particularly well-behaved in many ways: in particular, they are paracompact Hausdorff spaces (hence normal) and first-countable.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The Nagata–Smirnov metrization theorem gives a characterization of metrizability in terms of other topological properties, without reference to metrics.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] In metric spaces, both of these definitions make sense and they are equivalent.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] This is a general pattern for topological properties of metric spaces: while they can be defined in a purely topological way, there is often a way that uses the metric which is easier to state or more familiar from real analysis.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Informally, a metric space is *complete* if it has no "missing points": every sequence that looks like it should converge to something actually converges.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] To make this precise: a sequence (*xn*) in a metric space M is a Cauchy sequence if for every ε > 0 there is an integer N such that for all *m*, *n* > *N*, *d*(*xm*, *xn*) < ε.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] By the triangle inequality, any convergent sequence is a Cauchy sequence: if xm and xn are both less than ε away from the limit, then they are less than 2ε away from each other.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] If the converse is true—every Cauchy sequence in M converges—then M is complete.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Euclidean spaces are complete, as is $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ with the other metrics described above.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Two examples of spaces which are not complete are (0, 1) and the rationals, each with the metric induced from $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] One can think of (0, 1) as "missing" its endpoints 0 and 1.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The rationals are missing all the irrationals, since any irrational has a sequence of rationals converging to it in $\mathbb {R}$ (for example, its successive decimal approximations).
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] These examples show that completeness is *not* a topological property, since $\mathbb {R}$ is complete but the homeomorphic space (0, 1) is not.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] This notion of "missing points" can be made precise.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] In fact, every metric space has a unique *completion*, which is a complete space that contains the given space as a dense subset.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, [0, 1] is the completion of (0, 1), and the real numbers are the completion of the rationals.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Since complete spaces are generally easier to work with, completions are important throughout mathematics.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, in abstract algebra, the *p*-adic numbers are defined as the completion of the rationals under a different metric.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Completion is particularly common as a tool in functional analysis.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Often one has a set of nice functions and a way of measuring distances between them.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Taking the completion of this metric space gives a new set of functions which may be less nice, but nevertheless useful because they behave similarly to the original nice functions in important ways.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, weak solutions to differential equations typically live in a completion (a Sobolev space) rather than the original space of nice functions for which the differential equation actually makes sense.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] A metric space M is *bounded* if there is an r such that no pair of points in M is more than distance r apart.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The least such r is called the diameter of M.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The space M is called *precompact* or *totally bounded* if for every *r* > 0 there is a finite cover of M by open balls of radius r.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] To see this, start with a finite cover by r-balls for some arbitrary r.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Since the subset of M consisting of the centers of these balls is finite, it has finite diameter, say D.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] By the triangle inequality, the diameter of the whole space is at most *D* + 2*r*.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The converse does not hold: an example of a metric space that is bounded but not totally bounded is $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ (or any other infinite set) with the discrete metric.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Compactness is a topological property which generalizes the properties of a closed and bounded subset of Euclidean space.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] A metric space M is compact if every sequence has a convergent subsequence.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] A metric space M is compact if it is complete and totally bounded.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] One example of a compact space is the closed interval [0, 1].
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Compactness is important for similar reasons to completeness: it makes it easy to find limits.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Another important tool is Lebesgue's number lemma, which shows that for any open cover of a compact space, every point is relatively deep inside one of the sets of the cover.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Unlike in the case of topological spaces or algebraic structures such as groups or rings, there is no single "right" type of structure-preserving function between metric spaces.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Instead, one works with different types of functions depending on one's goals.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The words "function" and "map" are used interchangeably.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] It follows from the metric space axioms that a distance-preserving function is injective.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] A bijective distance-preserving function is called an *isometry*.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] If there is an isometry between the spaces *M*1 and *M*2, they are said to be *isometric*.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Metric spaces that are isometric are essentially identical.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] On the other end of the spectrum, one can forget entirely about the metric structure and study continuous maps, which only preserve topological structure.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] There are several equivalent definitions of continuity for metric spaces.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] A *homeomorphism* is a continuous bijection whose inverse is also continuous; if there is a homeomorphism between *M*1 and *M*2, they are said to be *homeomorphic*.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Homeomorphic spaces are the same from the point of view of topology, but may have very different metric properties.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, $\mathbb {R}$ is unbounded and complete, while (0, 1) is bounded but not complete.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The only difference between this definition and the ε–δ definition of continuity is the order of quantifiers: the choice of δ must depend only on ε and not on the point x.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] However, this subtle change makes a big difference.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, uniformly continuous maps take Cauchy sequences in *M*1 to Cauchy sequences in *M*2.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] In other words, uniform continuity preserves some metric properties which are not purely topological.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] On the other hand, the Heine–Cantor theorem states that if *M*1 is compact, then every continuous map is uniformly continuous.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] In other words, uniform continuity cannot distinguish any non-topological features of compact metric spaces.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] A Lipschitz map is one that stretches distances by at most a bounded factor.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, a curve in a metric space is rectifiable (has finite length) if and only if it has a Lipschitz reparametrization.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] A 1-Lipschitz map is sometimes called a *nonexpanding* or *metric map*.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Metric maps are commonly taken to be the morphisms of the category of metric spaces.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] A K-Lipschitz map for *K* < 1 is called a *contraction*.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The Banach fixed-point theorem states that if M is a complete metric space, then every contraction $f:M\to M$ admits a unique fixed point.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] A quasi-isometry is a map that preserves the "large-scale structure" of a metric space.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Quasi-isometries need not be continuous.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ and its subspace $\mathbb {Z} ^{2}$ are quasi-isometric, even though one is connected and the other is discrete.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The equivalence relation of quasi-isometry is important in geometric group theory: the Švarc–Milnor lemma states that all spaces on which a group acts geometrically are quasi-isometric.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] A normed vector space is a vector space equipped with a *norm*, which is a function that measures the length of vectors.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The norm of a vector v is typically denoted by $\lVert v\rVert$ .
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Any normed vector space can be equipped with a metric in which the distance between two vectors x and y is given by $d(x,y):=\lVert x-y\rVert .$ The metric d is said to be *induced* by the norm $\lVert {\cdot }\rVert$ .
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] then ${\displaystyle \lVert x\rVert$ is a norm induced by the metric.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] A similar relationship holds between seminorms and pseudometrics.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Among examples of metrics induced by a norm are the metrics *d*1, *d*2, and *d*∞ on $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ , which are induced by the Manhattan norm, the Euclidean norm, and the maximum norm, respectively.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] More generally, the Kuratowski embedding allows one to see any metric space as a subspace of a normed vector space.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Infinite-dimensional normed vector spaces, particularly spaces of functions, are studied in functional analysis.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Completeness is particularly important in this context: a complete normed vector space is known as a Banach space.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] An unusual property of normed vector spaces is that linear transformations between them are continuous if and only if they are Lipschitz.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Such transformations are known as bounded operators.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] A curve in a metric space (*M*, *d*) is a continuous function ${\displaystyle \gamma$ .
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The length of γ is measured by $L(\gamma )=\sup _{0=x_{0}<x_{1}<\cdots <x_{n}=T}\left\{\sum _{k=1}^{n}d(\gamma (x_{k-1}),\gamma (x_{k}))\right\}.$ In general, this supremum may be infinite; a curve of finite length is called *rectifiable*.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Suppose that the length of the curve γ is equal to the distance between its endpoints—that is, it is the shortest possible path between its endpoints.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] After reparametrization by arc length, γ becomes a *geodesic*: a curve which is a distance-preserving function.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] A geodesic is a shortest possible path between any two of its points.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] A *geodesic metric space* is a metric space which admits a geodesic between any two of its points.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] In $(\mathbb {R} ^{2},d_{2})$ , geodesics are unique, but in $(\mathbb {R} ^{2},d_{1})$ , there are often infinitely many geodesics between two points, as shown in the figure at the top of the article.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The space M is a *length space* (or the metric d is *intrinsic*) if the distance between any two points x and y is the infimum of lengths of paths between them.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Unlike in a geodesic metric space, the infimum does not have to be attained.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] An example of a length space which is not geodesic is the Euclidean plane minus the origin: the points (1, 0) and (-1, 0) can be joined by paths of length arbitrarily close to 2, but not by a path of length 2.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] An example of a metric space which is not a length space is given by the straight-line metric on the sphere: the straight line between two points through the center of the Earth is shorter than any path along the surface.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Given any metric space (*M*, *d*), one can define a new, intrinsic distance function *d*intrinsic on M by setting the distance between points x and y to be the infimum of the d-lengths of paths between them.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] For instance, if d is the straight-line distance on the sphere, then *d*intrinsic is the great-circle distance.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] However, in some cases *d*intrinsic may have infinite values.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, if M is the Koch snowflake with the subspace metric d induced from $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ , then the resulting intrinsic distance is infinite for any pair of distinct points.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] A Riemannian manifold is a space equipped with a Riemannian metric tensor, which determines lengths of tangent vectors at every point.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] This can be thought of defining a notion of distance infinitesimally.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] This construction generalizes to other kinds of infinitesimal metrics on manifolds, such as sub-Riemannian and Finsler metrics.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The Riemannian metric is uniquely determined by the distance function; this means that in principle, all information about a Riemannian manifold can be recovered from its distance function.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] One direction in metric geometry is finding purely metric ("synthetic") formulations of properties of Riemannian manifolds.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, a Riemannian manifold is a CAT(*k*) space (a synthetic condition which depends purely on the metric) if and only if its sectional curvature is bounded above by k.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Thus CAT(*k*) spaces generalize upper curvature bounds to general metric spaces.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Real analysis makes use of both the metric on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ and the Lebesgue measure.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Therefore, generalizations of many ideas from analysis naturally reside in metric measure spaces: spaces that have both a measure and a metric which are compatible with each other.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Formally, a *metric measure space* is a metric space equipped with a Borel regular measure such that every ball has positive measure.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] For example Euclidean spaces of dimension n, and more generally n-dimensional Riemannian manifolds, naturally have the structure of a metric measure space, equipped with the Lebesgue measure.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Certain fractal metric spaces such as the Sierpiński gasket can be equipped with the α-dimensional Hausdorff measure where α is the Hausdorff dimension.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] In general, however, a metric space may not have an "obvious" choice of measure.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] One application of metric measure spaces is generalizing the notion of Ricci curvature beyond Riemannian manifolds.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Just as CAT(*k*) and Alexandrov spaces generalize sectional curvature bounds, RCD spaces are a class of metric measure spaces which generalize lower bounds on Ricci curvature.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] A metric space is *discrete* if its induced topology is the discrete topology.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Although many concepts, such as completeness and compactness, are not interesting for such spaces, they are nevertheless an object of study in several branches of mathematics.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] In particular, finite metric spaces (those having a finite number of points) are studied in combinatorics and theoretical computer science.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Embeddings in other metric spaces are particularly well-studied.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, not every finite metric space can be isometrically embedded in a Euclidean space or in Hilbert space.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] On the other hand, in the worst case the required distortion (bilipschitz constant) is only logarithmic in the number of points.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] For any undirected connected graph G, the set V of vertices of G can be turned into a metric space by defining the distance between vertices x and y to be the length of the shortest edge path connecting them.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] In graph theory, this is also called the shortest-path distance or geodesic distance.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] In geometric group theory this construction is applied to the Cayley graph of a (typically infinite) finitely-generated group, yielding the word metric.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Up to quasi-isometry, the word metric depends only on the group and not on the chosen finite generating set.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] An important area of study in finite metric spaces is the embedding of complex metric spaces into simpler ones while controlling the distortion of distances.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] This is particularly useful in computer science and discrete mathematics, where algorithms often perform more efficiently on simpler structures like tree metrics.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] A significant result in this area is that any finite metric space can be probabilistically embedded into a *tree metric* with an expected distortion of $O(\log n)$ , where n is the number of points in the metric space.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] This embedding is notable because it achieves the best possible asymptotic bound on distortion, matching the lower bound of $\Omega (\log n)$ .
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The tree metrics produced in this embedding *dominate* the original metrics, meaning that distances in the tree are greater than or equal to those in the original space.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] This property is particularly useful for designing approximation algorithms, as it allows for the preservation of distance-related properties while simplifying the underlying structure.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The technique involves constructing a hierarchical decomposition of the original metric space and converting it into a tree metric via a randomized algorithm.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The $O(\log n)$ distortion bound has led to improved approximation ratios in several algorithmic problems, demonstrating the practical significance of this theoretical result.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] In modern mathematics, one often studies spaces whose points are themselves mathematical objects.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] A distance function on such a space generally aims to measure the dissimilarity between two objects.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The idea of spaces of mathematical objects can also be applied to subsets of a metric space, as well as metric spaces themselves.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Hausdorff and Gromov–Hausdorff distance define metrics on the set of compact subsets of a metric space and the set of compact metric spaces, respectively.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Suppose (*M*, *d*) is a metric space, and let S be a subset of M.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The *distance from S to a point x of M* is, informally, the distance from x to the closest point of S.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] However, since there may not be a single closest point, it is defined via an infimum: $d(x,S)=\inf\{d(x,s):s\in S\}.$ In particular, $d(x,S)=0$ if and only if x belongs to the closure of S.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Furthermore, distances between points and sets satisfy a version of the triangle inequality: $d(x,S)\leq d(x,y)+d(y,S),$ and therefore the map $d_{S}:M\to \mathbb {R}$ defined by $d_{S}(x)=d(x,S)$ is continuous.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Incidentally, this shows that metric spaces are completely regular.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Given two subsets S and T of M, their *Hausdorff distance* is $d_{H}(S,T)=\max\{\sup\{d(s,T):s\in S\},\sup\{d(t,S):t\in T\}\}.$ Informally, two sets S and T are close to each other in the Hausdorff distance if no element of S is too far from T and vice versa.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, if S is an open set in Euclidean space T is an ε-net inside S, then $d_{H}(S,T)<\varepsilon$ .
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] In general, the Hausdorff distance $d_{H}(S,T)$ can be infinite or zero.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] However, the Hausdorff distance between two distinct compact sets is always positive and finite.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Thus the Hausdorff distance defines a metric on the set of compact subsets of M.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The Gromov–Hausdorff metric defines a distance between (isometry classes of) compact metric spaces.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The *Gromov–Hausdorff distance* between compact spaces X and Y is the infimum of the Hausdorff distance over all metric spaces Z that contain X and Y as subspaces.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] While the exact value of the Gromov–Hausdorff distance is rarely useful to know, the resulting topology has found many applications.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] By the equivalence of norms in finite dimensions, a topologically equivalent metric is obtained if N is the taxicab norm, a p-norm, the maximum norm, or any other norm which is non-decreasing as the coordinates of a positive n-tuple increase (yielding the triangle inequality).
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The topological product of uncountably many metric spaces need not be metrizable.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, an uncountable product of copies of $\mathbb {R}$ is not first-countable and thus is not metrizable.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] If M is a metric space with metric d, and $\sim$ is an equivalence relation on M, then we can endow the quotient set $M/\!\sim$ with a pseudometric.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] In general this will only define a pseudometric, i.e. $d'([x],[y])=0$ does not necessarily imply that $[x]=[y]$ .
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] However, for some equivalence relations (e.g., those given by gluing together polyhedra along faces), $d'$ is a metric.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The quotient metric $d'$ is characterized by the following universal property.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] The quotient metric does not always induce the quotient topology.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, the topological quotient of the metric space $\mathbb {N} \times [0,1]$ identifying all points of the form $(n,0)$ is not metrizable since it is not first-countable, but the quotient metric is a well-defined metric on the same set which induces a coarser topology.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] Moreover, different metrics on the original topological space (a disjoint union of countably many intervals) lead to different topologies on the quotient.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p01] A topological space is sequential if and only if it is a (topological) quotient of a metric space.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] There are several notions of spaces which have less structure than a metric space, but more than a topological space.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] There are also numerous ways of relaxing the axioms for a metric, giving rise to various notions of generalized metric spaces.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] These generalizations can also be combined.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] The terminology used to describe them is not completely standardized.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] Most notably, in functional analysis pseudometrics often come from seminorms on vector spaces, and so it is natural to call them "semimetrics".
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] This conflicts with the use of the term in topology.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] Some authors define metrics so as to allow the distance function d to attain the value ∞, i.e. distances are non-negative numbers on the extended real number line.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] Such a function is also called an *extended metric* or "∞-metric".
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] Every extended metric can be replaced by a real-valued metric that is topologically equivalent.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] This can be done using a subadditive monotonically increasing bounded function which is zero at zero, e.g. $d'(x,y)=d(x,y)/(1+d(x,y))$ or $d''(x,y)=\min(1,d(x,y))$ .
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] These generalizations still induce a uniform structure on the space.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] A *pseudometric* on X is a function $d:X\times X\to \mathbb {R}$ which satisfies the axioms for a metric, except that instead of the second (identity of indiscernibles) only $d(x,x)=0$ for all *x* is required.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] In some contexts, pseudometrics are referred to as *semimetrics* because of their relation to seminorms.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] Occasionally, a **quasimetric** is defined as a function that satisfies all axioms for a metric with the possible exception of symmetry.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] The name of this generalisation is not entirely standardized.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] For example, given a set X of mountain villages, the typical walking times between elements of X form a quasimetric because travel uphill takes longer than travel downhill.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] Another example is the length of car rides in a city with one-way streets: here, a shortest path from point A to point B goes along a different set of streets than a shortest path from B to A and may have a different length.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] A quasimetric on the reals can be defined by setting $d(x,y)={\begin{cases}x-y&{\text{if }}x\geq y,\\1&{\text{otherwise.}}\end{cases}}$ The 1 may be replaced, for example, by infinity or by $1+{\sqrt {y-x}}$ or any other subadditive function of *y*-*x*.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] This quasimetric describes the cost of modifying a metal stick: it is easy to reduce its size by filing it down, but it is difficult or impossible to grow it.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] Given a quasimetric on X, one can define an R-ball around x to be the set $\{y\in X|d(x,y)\leq R\}$ .
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] As in the case of a metric, such balls form a basis for a topology on X, but this topology need not be metrizable.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] For example, the topology induced by the quasimetric on the reals described above is the (reversed) Sorgenfrey line.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] In a *metametric*, all the axioms of a metric are satisfied except that the distance between identical points is not necessarily zero.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] Metametrics appear in the study of Gromov hyperbolic metric spaces and their boundaries.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] The *visual metametric* on such a space satisfies $d(x,x)=0$ for points x on the boundary, but otherwise $d(x,x)$ is approximately the distance from *x* to the boundary.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] Metametrics were first defined by Jussi Väisälä.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] In other work, a function satisfying these axioms is called a *partial metric* or a *dislocated metric*.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] The ρ-inframetric inequality implies the ρ-relaxed triangle inequality (assuming the first axiom), and the ρ-relaxed triangle inequality implies the 2ρ-inframetric inequality.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] Semimetrics satisfying these equivalent conditions have sometimes been referred to as *quasimetrics*, *nearmetrics* or **inframetrics**.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] The ρ-inframetric inequalities were introduced to model round-trip delay times in the internet.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] The triangle inequality implies the 2-inframetric inequality, and the ultrametric inequality is exactly the 1-inframetric inequality.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] Sometimes it is used to refer to other generalizations of metrics such as pseudosemimetrics or pseudometrics; in translations of Russian books it sometimes appears as "prametric".
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] A premetric that satisfies symmetry, i.e. a pseudosemimetric, is also called a distance.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] Any premetric gives rise to a topology as follows.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] A set is called *open* if for any point *p* in the set there is an r -ball centered at *p* which is contained in the set.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] Every premetric space is a topological space, and in fact a sequential space.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] In general, the r -balls themselves need not be open sets with respect to this topology.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] This defines a premetric on the power set of a premetric space.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] If we start with a (pseudosemi-)metric space, we get a pseudosemimetric, i.e. a symmetric premetric.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] The prefixes *pseudo-*, *quasi-* and *semi-* can also be combined, e.g., a **pseudoquasimetric** (sometimes called **hemimetric**) relaxes both the indiscernibility axiom and the symmetry axiom and is simply a premetric satisfying the triangle inequality.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] For pseudoquasimetric spaces the open r -balls form a basis of open sets.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] A very basic example of a pseudoquasimetric space is the set $\{0,1\}$ with the premetric given by $d(0,1)=1$ and $d(1,0)=0.$ The associated topological space is the Sierpiński space.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] Sets equipped with an extended pseudoquasimetric were studied by William Lawvere as "generalized metric spaces".
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] From a categorical point of view, the extended pseudometric spaces and the extended pseudoquasimetric spaces, along with their corresponding nonexpansive maps, are the best behaved of the metric space categories.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] One can take arbitrary products and coproducts and form quotient objects within the given category.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] If one drops "extended", one can only take finite products and coproducts.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] If one drops "pseudo", one cannot take quotients.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] Lawvere also gave an alternate definition of such spaces as enriched categories.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] The ordered set $(\mathbb {R} ,\geq )$ can be seen as a category with one morphism $a\to b$ if $a\geq b$ and none otherwise.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] Using + as the tensor product and 0 as the identity makes this category into a monoidal category $R^{*}$ .
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] The notion of a metric can be generalized from a distance between two elements to a number assigned to a multiset of elements.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] A multiset is a generalization of the notion of a set in which an element can occur more than once.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] Define the multiset union $U=XY$ as follows: if an element x occurs m times in X and n times in Y then it occurs *m* + *n* times in U.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] By considering the cases of axioms 1 and 2 in which the multiset X has two elements and the case of axiom 3 in which the multisets X, Y, and Z have one element each, one recovers the usual axioms for a metric.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] That is, every multiset metric yields an ordinary metric when restricted to sets of two elements.
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] A simple example is the set of all nonempty finite multisets X of integers with $d(X)=\max(X)-\min(X)$ .
[src:metrics-cardinality/metric-mathematics-p02] More complex examples are information distance in multisets; and normalized compression distance (NCD) in multisets.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] In software engineering, more specifically in distributed computing, **observability** is the ability to collect data about programs' execution, modules' internal states, and the communication among components.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] To improve observability, software engineers use a wide range of logging and tracing techniques to gather telemetry information, and tools to analyze and use it.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Observability is foundational to site reliability engineering, as it is the first step in triaging a service outage.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] One of the goals of observability is to minimize the amount of prior knowledge needed to debug an issue.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] The term is borrowed from control theory, where the "observability" of a system measures how well its state can be determined from its outputs.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Similarly, software observability measures how well a system's state can be understood from the obtained telemetry (metrics, logs, traces, profiling).
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] The term is frequently referred to as its numeronym **o11y** (where 11 stands for the number of letters between the first letter and the last letter of the word).
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] This is similar to other computer science abbreviations such as i18n and l10n and k8s.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Observability and monitoring are sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] As tooling, commercial offerings and practices evolved in complexity, "monitoring" was re-branded as observability in order to differentiate new tools from the old.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] The terms are commonly contrasted in that systems are *monitored* using predefined sets of *telemetry*, and monitored systems may be *observable*.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Majors et al. suggest that engineering teams that only have monitoring tools end up relying on expert foreknowledge (seniority), whereas teams that have observability tools rely on exploratory analysis (curiosity).
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Observability relies on three main types of telemetry data: metrics, logs and traces.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Those are often referred to as "pillars of observability".
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] A metric is a point in time measurement (scalar) that represents some system state.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Monitoring tools are typically configured to emit alerts when certain metric values exceed set thresholds.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Thresholds are set based on knowledge about normal operating conditions and experience.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Metrics are typically tagged to facilitate grouping and searchability.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Application developers choose what kind of metrics to instrument their software with, before it is released.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] As a result, when a previously unknown issue is encountered, it is impossible to add new metrics without shipping new code.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Furthermore, their cardinality can quickly make the storage size of telemetry data prohibitively expensive.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Since metrics are cardinality-limited, they are often used to represent aggregate values (for example: average page load time, or 5-second average of the request rate).
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Without external context, it is impossible to correlate between events (such as user requests) and distinct metric values.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Logs, or log lines, are generally free-form, unstructured text blobs that are intended to be human readable.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Modern logging is structured to enable machine parsability.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] As with metrics, an application developer must instrument the application upfront and ship new code if different logging information is required.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Logs typically include a timestamp and severity level.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] An event (such as a user request) may be fragmented across multiple log lines and interweave with logs from concurrent events.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] A cloud native application is typically made up of distributed services which together fulfill a single request.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] A distributed trace is an interrelated series of discrete events (also called spans) that track the progression of a single user request.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] A trace shows the causal and temporal relationships between the services that interoperate to fulfill a request.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Instrumenting an application with traces means sending span information to a tracing backend.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] The tracing backend correlates the received spans to generate presentable traces.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] To be able to follow a request as it traverses multiple services, spans are labeled with unique identifiers that enable constructing a parent-child relationship between spans.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Span information is typically shared in the HTTP headers of outbound requests.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Continuous profiling is another telemetry type used to precisely determine how an application consumes resources.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] To be able to observe an application, telemetry about the application's behavior needs to be collected or exported.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Instrumentation means generating telemetry alongside the normal operation of the application.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Telemetry is then collected by an independent backend for later analysis.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Instrumentation can be automatic, or custom.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Automatic instrumentation offers blanket coverage and immediate value; custom instrumentation brings higher value but requires more intimate involvement with the instrumented application.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Instrumentation can be native - done in-code (modifying the code of the instrumented application) - or out-of-code (e.g. sidecar, eBPF).
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Verifying new features in production by shipping them together with custom instrumentation is a practice called "observability-driven development".
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Metrics, logs and traces are most commonly listed as the pillars of observability.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Self monitoring is a practice where observability stacks monitor each other, in order to reduce the risk of inconspicuous outages.
[src:metrics-cardinality/observability-software] Self monitoring may be put in place in addition to high availability and redundancy to further avoid correlated failures.
[src:metrics-cardinality/practices-naming] The metric and label conventions presented in this document are not required for using Prometheus, but can serve as both a style-guide and a collection of best practices.
[src:metrics-cardinality/practices-naming] Individual organizations may want to approach some of these practices, e.g. naming conventions, differently.
[src:metrics-cardinality/practices-naming] As a rule of thumb, either the `sum()` or the `avg()` over all dimensions of a given metric should be meaningful (though not necessarily useful).
[src:metrics-cardinality/practices-naming] If it is not meaningful, split the data up into multiple metrics.
[src:metrics-cardinality/practices-naming] For example, having the capacity of various queues in one metric is good, while mixing the capacity of a queue with the current number of elements in the queue is not.
[src:metrics-cardinality/practices-naming] OpenTelemetry) do not recommend or even do not allow including information about a metric unit and type in the metric name.
[src:metrics-cardinality/practices-naming] A common argument is that those pieces of information are already defined somewhere else (e.g. schema, metadata, other labels, etc.).
[src:metrics-cardinality/practices-naming] Do not put the label names in the metric name, as this introduces redundancy and will cause confusion if the respective labels are aggregated away.
[src:metrics-cardinality/practices-naming] Prometheus does not have any units hard coded.
[src:metrics-cardinality/practices-naming] For better compatibility, base units should be used.
[src:metrics-cardinality/practices-naming] The following lists some metrics families with their base unit.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series-database] A **time series database** is a software system that is optimized for storing and serving time series through associated pairs of time(s) and value(s).
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series-database] In some fields, *time series* may be called profiles, curves, traces or trends.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series-database] Several early time series databases are associated with industrial applications which could efficiently store measured values from sensory equipment (also referred to as data historians), but now are used in support of a much wider range of applications.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series-database] In many cases, the repositories of time-series data will utilize compression algorithms to manage the data efficiently.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series-database] Although it is possible to store time-series data in many different database types, the design of these systems with time as a key index is distinctly different from relational databases which reduce discrete relationships through referential models.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series-database] Time series datasets are relatively large and uniform compared to other datasets―usually being composed of a timestamp and associated data.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series-database] Time series datasets can also have fewer relationships between data entries in different tables and don't require indefinite storage of entries.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series-database] The unique properties of time series datasets mean that time series databases can provide significant improvements in storage space and performance over general purpose databases.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series-database] For instance, due to the uniformity of time series data, specialized compression algorithms can provide improvements over regular compression algorithms designed to work on less uniform data.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series-database] Time series databases can also be configured to regularly delete (or downsample) old data, unlike regular databases which are designed to store data indefinitely.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series-database] Special database indices can also provide boosts in query performance.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series-database] Time series databases are commonly designed for append-heavy workloads, where large numbers of measurements or events are continuously written together with timestamps.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series-database] Specialized time series management systems have been developed for data from monitoring, automation, the Internet of Things, and cyber-physical systems, where data may be produced at high velocity and in large volumes.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series-database] Common design goals include high-throughput data ingestion, low-latency queries over time ranges, efficient compression, and support for aggregation or downsampling over time windows.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series-database] Many systems also organize data by tags, devices, sensors, or other metadata, so that users can retrieve measurements by both time range and source.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series-database] Time series databases are used in application areas where data is collected continuously over time.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series-database] Examples include industrial monitoring, operational historians, infrastructure and application monitoring, Internet of Things sensor data, energy systems, financial market data, and scientific measurements.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series-database] In monitoring applications, time series database systems may need to process large amounts of sensor or metric data in real time, execute continuous queries, and support analytical tasks such as data exploration, anomaly detection, predictive modeling, trend analysis, and missing-value recovery.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series-database] Time series databases are often used as storage and query systems for downstream analytical tasks, including forecasting, anomaly detection, imputation, and pattern matching.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series-database] Some systems also integrate analytical or machine-learning functions closer to the database layer, allowing users to invoke forecasting or anomaly detection through database query interfaces such as SQL.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series-database] Recent research in time series analysis has also explored large pre-trained models for tasks such as forecasting, imputation, and anomaly detection.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series-database] These models are usually discussed as analytical methods for time series data rather than as defining features of time series databases.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series-database] The following database systems have functionality optimized for handling time series data.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] In mathematics, a **time series** is a sequence of data points indexed, listed, or graphed in chronological order.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Most commonly, a time series consists of observations recorded at successive equally spaced points in time.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Thus, it represents a form of discrete-time data.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] A time series may describe measurements collected over seconds, days, years, or even centuries.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Common examples include heights of ocean tides, counts of sunspots, daily temperature readings, and the closing values of stock market indices such as the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] A time series is often visualized using a run chart (a type of temporal line chart), which helps identify patterns such as trends, seasonal effects, and irregular fluctuations.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Time series data have a natural temporal ordering.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] This makes time series analysis distinct from cross-sectional studies, in which there is no natural ordering of the observations (e.g. explaining people's wages by reference to their respective education levels, where the individuals' data could be entered in any order).
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Time series analysis is also distinct from spatial data analysis where the observations typically relate to geographical locations (e.g. accounting for house prices by the location as well as the intrinsic characteristics of the houses).
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] A stochastic model for a time series will generally reflect the fact that observations close together in time will be more closely related than observations further apart.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] In addition, time series models will often make use of the natural one-way ordering of time so that values for a given period will be expressed as deriving in some way from past values, rather than from future values (see time reversibility).
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Time series analysis can be applied to real-valued, continuous data, discrete numeric data, or discrete symbolic data (i.e. sequences of characters, such as letters and words in the English language).
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Methods for time series analysis may be divided into two classes: frequency-domain methods and time-domain methods.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] The former include spectral analysis and wavelet analysis; the latter include auto-correlation and cross-correlation analysis.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] In the time domain, correlation and analysis can be made in a filter-like manner using scaled correlation, thereby mitigating the need to operate in the frequency domain.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Additionally, time series analysis techniques may be divided into parametric and non-parametric methods.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] The parametric approaches assume that the underlying stationary stochastic process has a certain structure which can be described using a small number of parameters (for example, using an autoregressive or moving-average model).
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] In these approaches, the task is to estimate the parameters of the model that describes the stochastic process.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] By contrast, non-parametric approaches explicitly estimate the covariance or the spectrum of the process without assuming that the process has any particular structure.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Methods of time series analysis may also be divided into linear and non-linear, and univariate and multivariate.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] A time series is one type of panel data.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Panel data is the general class, a multidimensional data set, whereas a time series data set is a one-dimensional panel (as is a cross-sectional dataset).
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] A data set may exhibit characteristics of both panel data and time series data.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] One way to tell is to ask what makes one data record unique from the other records.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] If the answer is the time data field, then this is a time series data set candidate.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] If determining a unique record requires a time data field and an additional identifier which is unrelated to time (e.g. student ID, stock symbol, country code), then it is panel data candidate.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] If the differentiation lies on the non-time identifier, then the data set is a cross-sectional data set candidate.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] There are several types of motivation and data analysis available for time series which are appropriate for different purposes.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] In the context of statistics, econometrics, quantitative finance, seismology, meteorology, and geophysics the primary goal of time series analysis is forecasting.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] In the context of signal processing, control engineering and communication engineering it is used for signal detection.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Other applications are in data mining, pattern recognition and machine learning, where time series analysis can be used for clustering, classification, query by content, anomaly detection as well as forecasting.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] A simple way to examine a regular time series is manually with a line chart.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] The datagraphic shows tuberculosis deaths in the United States, along with the yearly change and the percentage change from year to year.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] The total number of deaths declined in every year until the mid-1980s, after which there were occasional increases, often proportionately - but not absolutely - quite large.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] A study of corporate data analysts found two challenges to exploratory time series analysis: discovering the shape of interesting patterns, and finding an explanation for these patterns.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Visual tools that represent time series data as heat map matrices can help overcome these challenges.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] This approach may be based on harmonic analysis and filtering of signals in the frequency domain using the Fourier transform, and spectral density estimation.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Its development was significantly accelerated during World War II by mathematician Norbert Wiener, electrical engineers Rudolf E.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Kálmán, Dennis Gabor and others for filtering signals from noise and predicting signal values at a certain point in time.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] An equivalent effect may be achieved in the time domain, as in a Kalman filter; see filtering and smoothing for more techniques.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Curve fitting is the process of constructing a curve, or mathematical function, that has the best fit to a series of data points, possibly subject to constraints.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Curve fitting can involve either interpolation, where an exact fit to the data is required, or smoothing, in which a "smooth" function is constructed that approximately fits the data.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] A related topic is regression analysis, which focuses more on questions of statistical inference such as how much uncertainty is present in a curve that is fit to data observed with random errors.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Fitted curves can be used as an aid for data visualization, to infer values of a function where no data are available, and to summarize the relationships among two or more variables.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Extrapolation refers to the use of a fitted curve beyond the range of the observed data, and is subject to a degree of uncertainty since it may reflect the method used to construct the curve as much as it reflects the observed data.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] For processes that are expected to generally grow in magnitude one of the curves in the graphic (and many others) can be fitted by estimating their parameters.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] The construction of economic time series involves the estimation of some components for some dates by interpolation between values ("benchmarks") for earlier and later dates.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Interpolation is estimation of an unknown quantity between two known quantities (historical data), or drawing conclusions about missing information from the available information ("reading between the lines").
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Interpolation is useful where the data surrounding the missing data is available and its trend, seasonality, and longer-term cycles are known.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] This is often done by using a related series known for all relevant dates.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Alternatively polynomial interpolation or spline interpolation is used where piecewise polynomial functions are fitted in time intervals such that they fit smoothly together.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] A different problem which is closely related to interpolation is the approximation of a complicated function by a simple function (also called regression).
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] The main difference between regression and interpolation is that polynomial regression gives a single polynomial that models the entire data set.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Spline interpolation, however, yield a piecewise continuous function composed of many polynomials to model the data set.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Extrapolation is the process of estimating, beyond the original observation range, the value of a variable on the basis of its relationship with another variable.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] It is similar to interpolation, which produces estimates between known observations, but extrapolation is subject to greater uncertainty and a higher risk of producing meaningless results.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] In general, a function approximation problem asks us to select a function among a well-defined class that closely matches ("approximates") a target function in a task-specific way.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Second, the target function, call it *g*, may be unknown; instead of an explicit formula, only a set of points (a time series) of the form (*x*, *g*(*x*)) is provided.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Depending on the structure of the domain and codomain of *g*, several techniques for approximating *g* may be applicable.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] For example, if *g* is an operation on the real numbers, techniques of interpolation, extrapolation, regression analysis, and curve fitting can be used.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] If the codomain (range or target set) of *g* is a finite set, one is dealing with a classification problem instead.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] A related problem of *online* time series approximation is to summarize the data in one-pass and construct an approximate representation that can support a variety of time series queries with bounds on worst-case error.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] To some extent, the different problems (regression, classification, fitness approximation) have received a unified treatment in statistical learning theory, where they are viewed as supervised learning problems.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] In statistics, prediction is a part of statistical inference.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] One particular approach to such inference is known as predictive inference, but the prediction can be undertaken within any of the several approaches to statistical inference.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Indeed, one description of statistics is that it provides a means of transferring knowledge about a sample of a population to the whole population, and to other related populations, which is not necessarily the same as prediction over time.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] When information is transferred across time, often to specific points in time, the process is known as forecasting.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Assigning time series pattern to a specific category, for example identify a word based on series of hand movements in sign language.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Splitting a time-series into a sequence of segments.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] It is often the case that a time-series can be represented as a sequence of individual segments, each with its own characteristic properties.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] For example, the audio signal from a conference call can be partitioned into pieces corresponding to the times during which each person was speaking.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] In time-series segmentation, the goal is to identify the segment boundary points in the time-series, and to characterize the dynamical properties associated with each segment.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] One can approach this problem using change-point detection, or by modeling the time-series as a more sophisticated system, such as a Markov jump linear system.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Time series data may be clustered, however special care has to be taken when considering subsequence clustering.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Subsequence time series clustering resulted in unstable (random) clusters *induced by the feature extraction* using chunking with sliding windows.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] It was found that the cluster centers (the average of the time series in a cluster - also a time series) follow an arbitrarily shifted sine pattern (regardless of the dataset, even on realizations of a random walk).
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] This means that the found cluster centers are non-descriptive for the dataset because the cluster centers are always nonrepresentative sine waves.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Models for time series data can have many forms and represent different stochastic processes.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] When modeling variations in the level of a process, three broad classes of practical importance are the *autoregressive* (AR) models, the *integrated* (I) models, and the *moving-average* (MA) models.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] These three classes depend *linearly* on previous data points.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Combinations of these ideas produce autoregressive moving-average (ARMA) and autoregressive integrated moving-average (ARIMA) models.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] The autoregressive fractionally integrated moving-average (ARFIMA) model generalizes the former three.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Another important generalization is the time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) model, in which the AR coefficients are allowed to change over time, enabling the model to capture evolving or non-stationary dynamics.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Extensions of these classes to deal with vector-valued data are available under the heading of multivariate time-series models and sometimes the preceding acronyms are extended by including an initial "V" for "vector", as in VAR for vector autoregression.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] For these models, the acronyms are extended with a final "X" for "exogenous".
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) models are especially useful for analyzing non-stationary time series in which the underlying dynamics evolve over time in complex ways, not limited to classical forms of variation such as trends or seasonal patterns.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] This flexibility makes them well suited to modeling structural changes, regime shifts, or gradual evolutions in a system's behavior.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Estimation of TVAR models typically involves methods such as kernel smoothing, recursive least squares, or Kalman filtering.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Non-linear dependence of the level of a series on previous data points is of interest, partly because of the possibility of producing a chaotic time series.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] However, more importantly, empirical investigations can indicate the advantage of using predictions derived from non-linear models, over those from linear models, as for example in nonlinear autoregressive exogenous models.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Among other types of non-linear time series models, there are models to represent the changes of variance over time (heteroskedasticity).
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] These models represent autoregressive conditional heteroskedasticity (ARCH) and the collection comprises a wide variety of representation (GARCH, TARCH, EGARCH, FIGARCH, CGARCH, etc.).
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Here changes in variability are related to, or predicted by, recent past values of the observed series.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] This is in contrast to other possible representations of locally varying variability, where the variability might be modeled as being driven by a separate time-varying process, as in a doubly stochastic model.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Multiscale (often referred to as multiresolution) techniques decompose a given time series, attempting to illustrate time dependence at multiple scales.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] See also Markov switching multifractal (MSMF) techniques for modeling volatility evolution.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] A hidden Markov model (HMM) is a statistical Markov model in which the system being modeled is assumed to be a Markov process with unobserved (hidden) states.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] An HMM can be considered as the simplest dynamic Bayesian network.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] HMM models are widely used in speech recognition, for translating a time series of spoken words into text.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Many of these models are collected in the python package sktime.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] A number of different notations are in use for time-series analysis.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Ergodicity implies stationarity, but the converse is not necessarily the case.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Stationarity is usually classified into strict stationarity and wide-sense or second-order stationarity.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Both models and applications can be developed under each of these conditions, although the models in the latter case might be considered as only partly specified.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] In addition, time-series analysis can be applied where the series are seasonally stationary or non-stationary.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Situations where the amplitudes of frequency components change with time can be dealt with in time-frequency analysis which makes use of a time–frequency representation of a time-series or signal.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Time series can be visualized with two categories of chart: Overlapping Charts and Separated Charts.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] Jevons was the first to study times series.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] In his book he examined a number of weekly financial time series between the years 1825 to 1860 inclusive.
[src:metrics-cardinality/time-series] These included times series of bankruptcies, currency circulation and discount rates.
